{[%evp 0,16,16,18,26,-11,-12,6,35,43,52,31,34,34,35,29,28,9,0]} 1. d4 {Welcome to our course, "Bogo-Indian for White," part of the "1.d4 According to Dreev" series! The Bogo-Indian is a highly practical and fascinating opening, gaining more and more popularity today. It is easy to play for Black and often leads to three-result positions, making it an appealing choice for many players. However, after completing this course, we are confident that facing the Bogo-Indian as White will become your favorite scenario—you will enjoy playing against it! What makes this course truly special is that we provide you with two strong options: 4.Bd2 and 4.Nd2. This flexibility allows you to choose based on your playing style or even your opponent's preferences. Studying the Bogo-Indian is essential for a 1.d4 player, just as learning the Ruy-Lopez is for a 1.e4 player. Mastering this opening will not only improve your ability to handle the Bogo-Indian but will also deepen your understanding of 1.d4 structures and greatly enhance your overall strategic skills.} Nf6 ({In the third part of this database, we will discuss} 1... e6 2. c4 Bb4+ {Because it is closely connected to the main Bogo-Indian lines covered in the previous two sections. While there will be plenty of room for creativity, we strongly recommend studying Sections 1 and 2 first before diving into this third one.}) 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 {The second part of the database, is about 4.Nd2, and it will be presented by GM Alexey Dreev.} (4. Bd2 {The first part of this database focuses on the 4.Bd2 option, and it will be presented by GM Pier Luigi Basso. Compared to 4.Nd2, 4.Bd2 is much more natural and easier to play. However, let me address this right away—there is a minor move order issue in our repertoire if Black responds with 4...Be7. We will discuss this in more detail in the 4...Be7 informational section.} Qe7 {Black's mainline, and it's extremely useful to study it because it will improve not only your opening preparation, but also your general chess understanding.} (4... Be7 {will be discussed in the Informational section.}) (4... c5 $5 {very interesting line; you can play it also for Black. I recommend to play the simplest and safest line:} 5. Bxb4 cxb4 6. a3 bxa3 7. Rxa3 {White has easy and pleasant play. More about it in Chapter 8.}) (4... a5 {it's a serious move, my recommendation is} 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 {[%csl Ga3,Ra5] and our hope is that a3+a5 inclusion is good for White. More about it in Chapter 7.}) (4... Bxd2+ {This is considered Black's most solid option.} 5. Qxd2 O-O 6. g3 {Now, Black has two different-in-style options:} d5 {Will be discussed in Chapter 6.} (6... d6 {will be discussed in Chapter 5.})) 5. g3 Nc6 {mainline and a very tricky move.} (5... O-O {and other sidelines will be examined in Chapter 4.}) 6. e3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ye3d4] my recommendation. The idea is to protect the vulnerable d4 pawn. I learned for the first time about this move after watching live the impressive game Anand-Kollars 2016. In Chapter 1 we will have a general introduction about this position.} ({after the natural} 6. Bg2 {Black plays} Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 Ne4 8. Qc2 Qb4+ {[%csl Rc4,Rd4] and it's not easy to defend for the check because of the vulnerable c4 and d4 pawns. White can still play 9.Kf1, but that's enough just for an interesting game, not for an advantage.}) 6... O-O 7. Bg2 Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 {Now, Black has two different-in-spirit options:} d5 {will be examined in Chapter 1.} (8... d6 {Will be examined in Chapter 2.})) 4... O-O {Black's most common continuation.} (4... b6 {this is Black's second most important move.} 5. a3 Bxd2+ {In Chapter 9, I will logically explain how we should recapture on d2, depending on Black's 4th move, as this decision plays a crucial role in the position.}) (4... c5 {old passive move. We will analyze it in Chapter 14.}) (4... a5 {This is a tricky move, and you should first study Chapter 12 before diving into it. We will cover it in Chapter 14.}) (4... d5 5. Qa4+ ({you can also play} 5. g3 {transposing in Catalan part 2, but 5.Qa4+ is more interesting right now.}) 5... Nc6 6. a3 {Chapter 14.}) (4... d6 {rare but interesting. This is one of the rare cases where I don't want to play 5.a3.} 5. g3 {will be my recommendation in Chapter 11.} ({after} 5. a3 Bxd2+ {we don't have a suitable recapture. Why? More about this in Chapter 11 :)})) 5. a3 Be7 (5... Bxd2+ {it's always a question to understand how should we recapture. You will see my opinion in Chapter 10.}) 6. e4 d5 {This was Black's old mainline, but it is very risky, which is why, in the last 3-4 years, Bogo-Indian players have been searching for new alternatives. We will examine this in Chapter 12.} (6... d6 {more solid than 6...d5, but a bit passive. Very often, we will have KID structures where Black's Be7 is misplaced. More about it in Chapter 13.}) 7. e5 {With this course, you’ll have a deep understanding of the Bogo-Indian and its structures, equipping you with a strong, flexible repertoire. Let’s begin!} *

