{[%evp 0,23,17,16,21,6,17,15,27,13,13,18,26,34,23,0,-1,-1,-1,10,19,-6,0,0,0,-27]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ {Welcome to the 15 minutes video about the Bogo Indian for White.} 4. Nbd2 {[%cal Ya2a3,Yb4d2,Yb4e7] is presented by Dreev in the second part of the database, and since it is more complicated to study and you have Dreev's opinion in the theoretical chapters, in the 15 minutes we will focus only on this move. In 90% of cases, we will play a3 at some moment, so Black has two conceptually different choices: to take on d2 or to retreat to e7.} (4. Bd2 {is presented by me in the first part of the database.} Be7 {is the problem that due to the move order, this is not part of our repertoire, but anyway 4.Bd2 is useful to study, I show you some interesting ideas there.}) 4... O-O {Flexible move.} (4... b6 {Black plays a hybrid version of Bogo/Queen's Indian.} 5. a3 Bxd2+ {Black's idea.} (5... Be7 {Of course, makes no sense now.} 6. e4 $16 {Huge advantage.}) 6. Nxd2 $5 {my recommendation. We step aside from the big theory and try to play something more interesting!} (6. Bxd2 {is an option, but we usually play this recapture, when Black commited to 0-0. Why?} Bb7 {The bishop on d2 stays bad, so naturally we want} 7. Bg5 {[%csl Ge8][%cal Gh7h6,Gg5h4,Gg7g5] But Black's king is still on e8, which means he can potentially play h6 followed by g5 at some point.}) (6. Qxd2 {The big mainline. Of course, you can play it, but it requires extensive study, and in my opinion, there is a specific line that poses a serious challenge.} Bb7 7. e3 d5 $5 {There are only 17 recorded games, but many strong Grandmasters have played it recently. It is difficult for White to find advantage, Alexey will explain this in great detail in the according chapter.}) 6... Bb7 {only logical move, otherwise we will continue with e2-e4.} 7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3 $5 {[%csl Yg2] We are ready to sacrifice g2.} Bxg2 {Black can of course take the pawn, but we sacrificed it for a good reason.} (8... d5 {[%csl Gd2] Compared to the 6.Qxd2 variation, we are now better prepared against d5 because, in the event of dxc4, we will always have the option to recapture with the knight.} 9. O-O dxc4 $6 {this approach was interesting when White's knight was on f3, but not here:} 10. Nxc4 $1 $14 {[%csl Gc4] A very good point of having the knight on d2.}) 9. Rg1 Bb7 10. b3 $5 $146 {This is my recommendation, and it's a novelty.} d6 (10... d5 {the best, according to the engine. I can understand it because Black wants to immediately block White's Bb2.} 11. Bb2 Nbd7 12. cxd5 $5 {I like this direction.} exd5 13. Qf3 $44 {[%cal Ge1c1] Very good compensation. It's an interesting position for sure.}) 11. Bb2 Nbd7 12. Qe2 $36 {[%cal Ge1c1] 000 next, and we have more than compensation.}) (4... d6 {Here it's clear more than anywhere, that Black is planning to take on d2.} 5. g3 {This is my recommendation against 4...d6.} ({First, let's discuss why we won’t play 5.a3} 5. a3 Bxd2+ {Now, we don't have a suitable recapture.} 6. Qxd2 {Probably now it is a good moment to take on d2 with the queen, but stil we prefer to avoid big theory.} (6. Nxd2 {We saw in the previous line that Nxd2 is not very interesting when Black has not played b6.} e5 $11) (6. Bxd2 b6 $5 {[%csl Gd2] As you already know, I don't like to play Bxd2 when Black's king is still on e8.})) 5... O-O {Mainline.} 6. Bg2 e5 $1 {This is the strongest move, very rare (only 4 games).} (6... Qe7 {Black's most common continuation, but I don't think that it's the best.} 7. O-O e5 8. Nb3 $14 {[%csl Rb4] Problems with Bb4.}) 7. O-O $5 {Maybe it makes sense to play 7.00 without accepting the sacrificed pawn.} (7. dxe5 {Alexey will show you that is not easy to get an advantage here.}) 7... Bxd2 (7... e4 {looks logical, but we have an interesting resource:} 8. a3 $1 {Fantastic.} exf3 9. Nxf3 {[%csl Rb4] suddenly, Black's bishop is trapped.} Ba5 10. b4 Bb6 11. c5 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Gg2] slightly better for White thanks to the two bishops.}) 8. Bxd2 $5 $146 e4 $1 9. Nh4 $5 {We try to get an interesting and complicated game.} d5 $1 {This is Black's idea, the same as after 9.Ne1.} 10. f3 {The position is new, and Black needs to find strong moves, just one example:} dxc4 11. Bg5 {and now, Black must find an only move:} e3 $1 {I don't think it will be easy for everyone to find it. But objectively, Black is doing fine, so 4..d6 followed by 6...e5 is a serious line.}) (4... c5 {Let's check the sidelines.} 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Bxd2 {With a pawn on c5, it is another story.} cxd4 7. Nxd4 d5 8. cxd5 Qxd5 (8... Nxd5 $2 {bad because of} 9. e4 $16 {[%cal Gd4b5]}) 9. e3 {and now, Black should be very careful.} Bd7 $1 {the best.} (9... O-O $6 {looks like it's Black's priority, but no!} 10. Bb4 Rd8 {allows} (10... Re8 11. Nb5 $1 $14) 11. Be7 $36 {[%cal Ge7f6] Black has some problems.}) 10. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Gd2b4,Gc1c5] Rc1 is a nice move because sometimes we will have Bb4-Rc5 ideas. Black is solid, but usually slightly worse.}) (4... d5 5. Qa4+ {The most principled continuation and objectively stronger.} ({Of course, you can play} 5. g3 {and directly transpose to our "Catalan part 2".}) 5... Nc6 6. a3 {[%csl Gc3,Rc6][%cal Gd2c4] And it is an improved version of the Ragozin, because the d2 stays well against dxc4-e5 plan, since White can recapture Nxc4.}) 5. a3 Be7 {Black's second concept.} (5... Bxd2+ {This variation may seem similar to the one we previously examined, 4...b6, but there are some important differences that are worth noting.} 6. Bxd2 {[%csl Rg8] Compared to the 4...b6 line, it's important to note that Black has already castled. Why? Because once we play Bg5, Black will no longer have the h6-g5 ideas available.} (6. Qxd2 {This is always excluded, because big theory, and also the line.} d5 7. e3 b6 {We spoke about this position in the 4...b6 line.}) (6. Nxd2 {was our move against 4...b6, but here it is less interesting:} d6 {Black just play d6-e5, and the knight on d2 is misplaced.} 7. e3 e5 $132 {No problem for Black.}) 6... b6 {Black's most common continuation.} 7. Bg5 Bb7 8. e3 d6 9. Bd3 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Rh7h6,Yg5h4,Rg7g5] It's important to note that Black cannot play h6-g5 with the king on g8. However, this option will become available as soon as White castles.} Nbd7 10. Nd2 $5 {The idea is to control the e4 square.} (10. O-O {But don't play 0-0, because h6-g5 is an option now.} h6 11. Bh4 g5 $1 12. Bg3 Ne4 $132 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gf7f5,Ye4g3] f5 next, and Black has a very good counterplay.}) 10... Bxg2 $6 {It's quite risky.} 11. Rg1 Bb7 12. Ne4 $1 $40 {Big atack.}) 6. e4 {[%csl Gc3,Rd2] Everything looks fantastic for White, except the knight on d2.} d5 {It was the main line a few years ago, but players tried to switch to something more practical.} (6... d6 {[%csl Ye7] A solid system. It somewhat resembles the King's Indian, except that Black's bishop is on e7 instead of g7.} 7. Bd3 {We think this is the best, Alexey will explain you why.} e5 $1 {Black can play this move immediately, and he should do it.} (7... Nbd7 {[%cal Ge6e5] If Black prepares e5, it is not so good because it is not needed.} 8. O-O e5 {We can play many moves. I like the useful} 9. h3 $5 Re8 10. Nb1 $146 {[%cal Gb1c3] We have time to improve our knight.} exd4 11. Nxd4 Bf8 12. Nc3 Nc5 13. Re1 Nxd3 14. Qxd3 $14 {Typical positional advantage.}) 8. O-O exd4 $1 {the most critical.} (8... Nfd7 {too passive:} 9. d5 {[%csl Re7] Good moment to play d5.} Nc5 10. Bc2 a5 11. b3 {[%cal Ra5a4] useful move against a4.} f5 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Bxf5 Rxf5 14. Rb1 $14 {We have a classical structure and a classical pressure.}) 9. Nxd4 Nfd7 {It's more interesting, because Bf6 ideas, but} (9... Nc6 $6 {is bad because White can} 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Nb3 $1 {[%csl Ya5,Gd4][%cal Gb3d4,Yb3a5] Fantastic idea. Our knight will go to a5 (or to d4 sometimes).} c5 12. Na5 $14 {[%csl Ya5,Rc6][%cal Gc1d2,Gd2c3,Gb2b4,Gf2f4,Rc8b7] The knight on a5 is very good.}) 10. f4 Bf6 11. N2f3 Nc6 12. Bc2 $14 {It must be slightly better for White.}) 7. e5 Nfd7 8. Bd3 $1 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gc7c5] You need to understand that Black has very good counterplay in the center, that's why we need to start to attack on the kingside.} c5 {As already mentioned, this is Black's idea. That's why} 9. h4 $1 {We continue in the spirit of the position. Now, Bxh7+ is already a deadly threat, for this reason Black has to immediately defend against it. The old move is 9...g6, but the best move is 9...h6.} h6 $1 {the best.} (9... Nc6 $4 {let me just show you that this loses immediately:} 10. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 11. Ng5+ $18 {game over.}) (9... g6 {[%csl Rg7,Rh6] Old way, but it's bad, because it weakens the dark squares.} 10. O-O {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gc1h6] And the game develops with} Nc6 11. Nb3 cxd4 12. Re1 Bxh4 13. Bh6 Re8 14. Qd2 $40 {[%cal Gd2f4] You will see about this more in the chapter, but g6 is bad.}) 10. Bb1 {[%cal Gd1c2] We prepare Qc2.} cxd4 $1 {Black should play concrete moves if he wants to survive.} 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Qc2 f5 13. Nb3 $1 {[%csl Ye5,Rf5][%cal Gb3d4,Gc1f4,Ye1g1,Yf1e1] Now that we have provoked the weakening move f7-f5, we completely change our game plan, shifting our focus to reclaiming the d4 square and consolidating the crucial e5 pawn. And we play for a positional advantage.} (13. exf6 $6 Nxf6 $11 {once again, Black is fine here.}) 13... Nc6 14. Bf4 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yf4e5] Of course, we must protect our e5 pawn.} d3 $1 {This is the only problematic move for us. But about this position, more in depth in the chapter. Engine will hold, but I think the line is still very promising for White.} *

