1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 {The first part of this database focuses on the 4.Bd2 option. Compared to 4.Nd2, 4.Bd2 is much more natural and easier to play. However, let me address this right away—there is a minor move order issue in our repertoire if Black responds with 4...Be7. We will discuss this in more detail in the 4...Be7 informational section.} Qe7 {Black's mainline, and it's extremely useful to study it because it will improve not only your opening preparation, but also your general chess understanding.} (4... Be7 {will be discussed in the Informational section.}) (4... c5 $5 {very interesting line; you can play it also for Black. I recommend to play the simplest and safest line:} 5. Bxb4 cxb4 6. a3 bxa3 7. Rxa3 {White has easy and pleasant play. More about it in Chapter 8.}) (4... a5 {it's a serious move, my recommendation is} 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 {[%csl Ga3,Ra5] and our hope is that a3+a5 inclusion is good for White. More about it in Chapter 7.}) (4... Bxd2+ {This is considered Black's most solid option.} 5. Qxd2 O-O 6. g3 {Now, Black has two different-in-style options:} d5 {Will be discussed in Chapter 6.} (6... d6 {will be discussed in Chapter 5.})) 5. g3 Nc6 {mainline and a very tricky move.} (5... O-O {and other sidelines will be examined in Chapter 4.}) 6. e3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ye3d4] my recommendation. The idea is to protect the vulnerable d4 pawn. I learned for the first time about this move after watching live the impressive game Anand-Kollars 2016. In Chapter 1 we will have a general introduction about this position.} ({after the natural} 6. Bg2 {Black plays} Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 Ne4 8. Qc2 Qb4+ {[%csl Rc4,Rd4] and it's not easy to defend for the check because of the vulnerable c4 and d4 pawns. White can still play 9.Kf1, but that's enough just for an interesting game, not for an advantage.}) 6... O-O 7. Bg2 Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 {Now, Black has two different-in-spirit options:} d5 {will be examined in Chapter 1.} (8... d6 {Will be examined in Chapter 2.}) *

