{[%evp 0,20,19,34,29,4,4,1,34,34,56,22,31,18,27,29,37,2,35,34,28,34,38]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 {[%csl Gb1,Yd7][%cal Yd7d5,Yb1d2,Yb1a3] The most popular move, by far.} 6. e3 $5 {Very rare move, and my recommendation. The idea is simple: to defend the d4 pawn.} (6. Bg2 {would be perfectly fine, if not for} Bxd2+ $1 7. Qxd2 {Logical response, but Black has the concrete} (7. Nbxd2 {[%csl Rd2] We don't want to commit our knight on d2, because it doesn't stay well against d6-e5 plan.} d6 8. O-O e5 {[%csl Gc3,Rd2] And here the best move is} 9. Nb1 $11 {But clearly White's approach was not the best.}) 7... Ne4 $1 {Good move.} (7... O-O {If castle, everything is great for White.} 8. O-O d5 (8... d6 9. Nc3 $14) 9. Qc3 $14 {[%cal Gb1d2]}) 8. Qc2 Qb4+ $1 {Important check.} 9. Kf1 $5 {is the best move, and a playable line, but I don't think White has chances for advantage.} (9. Nbd2 $6 {is not possible, because after} Nxd2 {Either d4 or c4 is dropping.} 10. Qxd2 (10. Nxd2 Nxd4 $15) 10... Qxc4 $15) (9. Nc3 Nxc3 10. Qxc3 {is nothing for White.} Qxc3+ 11. bxc3 Na5 12. Nd2 Rb8 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] Black has at least no problems.}) 9... d5 10. e3 dxc4 $1 {The strongest move.} (10... Qxc4+ $6 {This would be great for White.} 11. Qxc4 dxc4 12. Nbd2 $14 {White will regain c4 and play a slightly better endgame.}) 11. Kg1 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gg1h2]} O-O 12. h3 Nd6 13. Kh2 f6 $13 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gc6a5] New complicated position, 0.00 evaluation.}) (6. Nc3 {The main line.} O-O 7. Bg2 Bxc3 {The most played.} (7... d5 {[%csl Yc3] is also not a bad move, because the knight on c3 is not ideally placed against a pawn on d5.} 8. a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Ne4 10. Qc2 a5 $132 {Playable for both sides.}) 8. Bxc3 Ne4 9. Rc1 {The old main line.} d6 10. d5 {Critical move.} (10. O-O {If castle, Black is doing great.} e5 11. d5 Nb8 $11 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ye4c3,Gf7f5]}) 10... Nd8 $5 {The most precise, in my opinion.} 11. O-O f5 $5 {can be interesting.} (11... e5 12. c5 $13 {Almost nothing, but some play for White.}) 12. Nd2 Nxc3 13. Rxc3 e5 14. c5 Nf7 $132 {Not an easy position to fight for an advantage, Black has easy moves.}) (6. a3 {is the most standard example on how to learn Black's idea.} Bxd2+ {And depending on White's recapture, Black commits the d pawn.} 7. Nbxd2 (7. Qxd2 d5 $11 {[%cal Rb1d2]}) 7... d6 $11 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Ge6e5]}) 6... O-O 7. Bg2 {Now we can develop Bg2, because the pawn on d4 is extra protected.} Bxd2+ {Probably the best moment to take on d2.} (7... a5 {Black can't delay Bxd2 for too long.} 8. O-O d6 $4 {Already a losing move.} 9. Bc1 $1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ga2a3] The bishop is trapped.} a4 10. a3 Ba5 11. Qxa4 $18 {That's how I once won a game in Greece 2021.}) 8. Qxd2 $1 {For sure it's our response, because Black didn't commit the d pawn, so we also don't touch the b1 knight.} e5 {was once played against me, and since Black didn't spend a tempo on d6, I believe it's best to play for the good structure.} (8... b6 {is a possible sideline.} 9. O-O Bb7 10. Nc3 Na5 11. b3 {Normal moves.} Ne4 {is Black's idea.} 12. Qc2 Nxc3 13. Qxc3 Be4 14. Rad1 $14 {Long term slightly better for White.}) (8... Ne4 {is a harmless idea now.} 9. Qc2 Qb4+ {[%csl Ge3,Rg8]} (9... f5 {The knight is too early on e4, so White is happy after} 10. O-O d6 11. Nfd2 Nxd2 12. Qxd2 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3,Ge3e4,Gb2b4,Gb4b5]}) 10. Nbd2 Nxd2 11. Nxd2 $14 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ye3d4,Rc6d4] And thanks to the inclusion of e3 and 0-0, this is possible for White.}) 9. Nxe5 $1 {For safety, taking with the knight is more precise.} (9. dxe5 {There is nothing wrong with it now, but in other positions ...Ng4 can be strong.}) 9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 {Ng4 is not an idea, because of f4.} Qxe5 11. Nc3 {This is the ideal structure for White.} c6 (11... d6 {It's anyway hard to develop the c8 bishop.} 12. O-O c6 13. b3 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gf1e1,Ge3e4,Gf2f4] No games, but it is clear that White is better.}) 12. Rd1 Rd8 {Maybe my opponent wanted to play with d5, but I don't believe it is even good.} 13. Qd6 $5 {Maybe not the best, but I like endgames.} (13. O-O {Castle was perfectly fine.} d6 {Black has to play anyway with d6, so Rd8 was quite an empty idea.} (13... d5 $6 {is not good.} 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Qd4 $16 {d5 pawn will fall.}) 14. h3 {[%cal Rc8g4] Useful move, to stop Bg4 tempo.} Be6 15. b3 $14 {f4-e4 later. d5 is a questionable plan.}) 13... Qxd6 14. Rxd6 Ne8 {Black has to achieve d7-d6.} (14... Kf8 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gd7d6] I prefer this, but it is a matter of taste, for the engine is not a mistake.}) 15. Rd4 d6 16. O-O {For the engine is only +0.30, but over the board, you can play this position with big enjoyment.} Be6 17. b3 Rd7 {Natural move, but other plans were also possible.} 18. e4 (18. g4 $5 {[%cal Gg4g5] is an idea to be considered, to take more space on the kingside.}) 18... Rad8 19. f4 {f5 is a threat.} f6 {My opponent played a conservative move.} (19... f5 $1 {was probably the best, improving the situation.} 20. exf5 (20. Bh3 $5 {Maybe my opponent was scared of this move.} g6 21. exf5 gxf5 22. Re4 $5 $13 {And the position is tough to evaluate, for an engine, this is not too much.}) 20... Bxf5 $14 {Still, slightly worse, but nothing dramatic.}) 20. h3 Nc7 21. g4 {More space on the kingside.} Bf7 22. Rd2 Ne6 23. h4 {Prophylaxis against g5.} (23. Kh2 {Black has} g5 $1 {And some counterplay on the dark squares.} 24. f5 Nc5 $132 {The e5 square will be used sooner or later.}) 23... h6 (23... g5 {is another story now.} 24. f5 Nc5 25. hxg5 fxg5 26. b4 $16 {Completely different structure.}) 24. h5 {[%cal Rg7g5] Again preventing g5.} Nc7 25. Kh2 {I keep improving, and my opponent lost patience.} d5 $6 {Black had to keep waiting.} 26. exd5 cxd5 27. Rfd1 d4 $2 {was the decisive mistake.} (27... f5 $16 {was the last chance, but not easy to hold.}) 28. Ne2 f5 29. Rxd4 Rxd4 30. Rxd4 Rxd4 31. Nxd4 fxg4 32. Bxb7 $18 {And my pawns are more important.} Bxh5 33. Kg3 Kf7 34. Nc6 Bg6 35. Nxa7 Bb1 36. a4 Bc2 37. Nb5 Bxb3 38. a5 Kf6 39. Nxc7 Bxc4 40. Ba6 Bb3 41. Bf1 {Basso-Vignesh, 1-0, Forni di Sopra 2019.} *

