{[%evp 0,35,22,17,33,7,7,26,38,38,56,20,20,16,25,-7,21,-2,15,2,20,6,11,11,6,-2,5,13,13,13,13,-8,43,32,43,43,35,35]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 Nc6 {[%csl Gb1,Yd7][%cal Yd7d5,Yb1d2,Yb1a3]} 6. e3 O-O (6... Bxd2+ {I think if Black wants to play with d5, this is a more precise move order. Why?} 7. Qxd2 d5 8. Qc3 $5 {is my recommendation also here.} (8. Bg2 {If we play in the same way:} dxc4 9. O-O {Black doesn't waste time on 0-0.} e5 {And can play the immediate e5 instead.} (9... Rb8 10. Rc1 b5 11. a4 a6 12. axb5 axb5 13. b3) (9... O-O {is just transposition after} 10. Qc3 {Analyzed under 6...0-0.}) 10. dxe5 (10. d5 {In case of this, Black is in time to play} Nb4 $1 11. Nxe5 c3 $1 {Fantastic move.} 12. bxc3 {looks like the best.} Nbxd5 13. c4 {can be tried, but it's around equal:} (13. Bxd5 Qxe5 $11 {Black is doing absolutely great.}) 13... Nb4 14. Qc3 O-O 15. Nd2 Re8 {The structure is not the same as with the pawn on b2.} 16. Rfb1 Qxe5 17. Qxe5 Rxe5 18. Rxb4 c6 $11 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gd7c5] Equal endgame.}) 10... Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Qxe5 {This is again almost nothing.} 12. Rc1 (12. Na3 {Carlsen-Papaioannou.} c3 $1 $11 {is strong.}) 12... Be6 13. Qb4 {Against castle.} a5 14. Qxb7 O-O {This is the best solution for the engine:} 15. Nd2 Rab8 16. Qc6 Rxb2 17. Nxc4 Bxc4 18. Qxc4 g6 {Just useful move.} 19. Qxc7 Qf5 $44 {Black has compensation, also in the endgame.}) 8... Ne4 {We are happy to provoke it.} (8... dxc4 {makes no sense now.} 9. Nbd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2c4] No e5, definitely slightly better for White.}) (8... O-O 9. Bg2 dxc4 10. O-O {Transposes.} (10. Na3 $5 {Interesting extra option.})) 9. Qc2 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Rd5c4] More precise than on c1, because it also stops dxc4.} Nb4 $5 {[%csl Rb4,Re4] Black jumps two times with the knights, but maybe they are misplaced.} (9... O-O 10. a3 {To control the square.} Nf6 11. Nc3 Rd8 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Bg2 {Normal moves, it is not easy to play for Black:} Bg4 14. O-O a6 (14... Bh5 15. Nh4 $1 $14 {is the idea.}) 15. Rac1 $14 {[%csl Rc6] Good picture for us.}) 10. Qc1 $146 c5 $1 {The best move according to engine. Black has to justifiy his play.} (10... O-O {If castle, just} 11. a3 Nc6 12. Bg2 $14 {And Black lost time.}) 11. a3 Nc6 12. dxc5 {I prefer to take on c5.} (12. Bg2 {is one option, but I am not sure about the structure after cxd4.}) 12... O-O 13. Nbd2 Nxc5 (13... Qxc5 14. Bg2 $14 {playable.}) 14. b4 {Black can go to a4 or e4.} Ne4 {is the best.} (14... Na4 15. Bg2 $14 {[%csl Rc8,Gg2] Typically pleasant position for White.}) 15. Qb2 $5 {To introduce the Nxe4 idea.} (15. Bg2 {I don't like it.} Bd7 $132) (15. Nxe4 $6 {Not immediately, because after} dxe4 16. Nd2 Ne5 $1 $132 {[%csl Ge5] is a strong idea.}) 15... Nxd2 {Black can play something very solid like:} (15... Bd7 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Gb2,Re4][%cal Rc6e5] No Ne5, and some problems with the pawn.}) (15... Qf6 16. Qxf6 Nxf6 17. Bg2 $14 {More pleasant endgame.}) 16. Nxd2 dxc4 17. Bg2 $5 {is more interesting maybe.} (17. Bxc4 b6 18. O-O Bb7 19. Be2 $13 {Slightly more pleasant for White, and still playable.}) 17... Bd7 18. Nxc4 b5 $1 {Strong move.} 19. Nd2 $14 {An engine will equalize for sure, but practically it was not easy for Black to reach this position.}) 7. Bg2 Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 d5 9. O-O dxc4 {The critical move.} (9... Rd8 {[%cal Gb1d2] is a possible move, but maybe it is not always useful, while dxc4 is almost always played.} 10. Qc3 {The queen on c3 stays well, it stops e5, and we are always happy to provoke Ne4.} Bd7 {Normal moves.} (10... Ne4 {The knight stays bad here.} 11. Qc1 a5 12. Nfd2 {And we want to exchange a pair of knights.} Nf6 {loses a lot of tempi.} 13. Nc3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd2] The knight on c3 is okay now, since the other one is on d2.} dxc4 14. Nxc4 e5 15. d5 $14 {Definetely some advantage for White.}) 11. Nbd2 Be8 {[%cal Re6e5,Rd5c4,Gd2c4] And now we can wait, since Black has no useful plan.} 12. a3 a5 (12... a6 13. Rfe1 $14 {This is the type of positions a Bogo Indian player would like to avoid.}) 13. cxd5 $5 {becomes more interesting now, because} exd5 {[%csl Ra5] In this structure, a5 is not so great.} 14. Rfe1 $14) 10. Qc3 $5 {[%cal Re6e5] Today, this is my recommendation. The idea is to stop e5.} (10. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c4,Re6e5] For many years, I though this was the best move, the idea is to capture on c4 and get a tempo on the queen.} e5 {Black has to go for this.} 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Nxc4 {I prepared this line also for the young IM Barp.} Qe7 $1 {is the best move.} (13... Qh5 {was played in the game, but it is not the best, because of} 14. Qa5 $1 {Very strong move.} Qxa5 15. Nxa5 {[%csl Ga5,Ra7,Rb7,Rc7] The knight is fantastic against the structure.} c6 {[%csl Rb7,Rc6,Rc8][%cal Rb7b6,Rc6c5] has to be played, but now it is difficult to develop the bishop on c8, the pawns cannot be touched. White won the game in Barp-Sonis, Trieste 2017.}) 14. Qc3 {And my idea was:} c6 15. Qa3 $5 $146 {This was never tried.} Qxa3 16. bxa3 {[%cal Gc4a5,Ga1b1,Gf1c1] And White can play this endgame. 6-7 years ago, engine believed that White has some pressure, +0.20, but now the opinion has changed:} Nd5 (16... Bf5 $5 {This is also possible.} 17. Nd6 Bd3 18. Rfd1 Ba6 $11 {Black is equalizing.}) 17. Rfc1 Nb6 18. Na5 Rb8 19. Nb3 {White can transfer the knight, but it is still nothing.} (19. Rab1 Be6 $11 {No problem for Black.}) 19... Rd8 20. Nc5 Kf8 $11 {Should be an equal endgame.}) 10... Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5] I think this is the best move, tried only in Ragger-Moiseenko, and one email game. The idea is b5.} (10... Rd8 {The most common continuation.} 11. Na3 {We want to capture on c4 with the knight.} Nd5 12. Qc1 $1 {[%cal Ga3c4] Much more precise to take with the knight.} (12. Qxc4 Bd7 $132 {Playable for Black.}) 12... c3 $1 {Best move for Black.} (12... Bd7 13. Nxc4 $14 {[%cal Re6e5] This is of course, not what Black wants.}) (12... e5 $2 {was played in the game Kryakvin-Yuffa, but the move is bad.} 13. e4 $1 Nf6 $6 {is even worse.} (13... Nb6 {leads to a bad position after} 14. d5 Nb8 15. Nxc4 $16) 14. d5 Nb8 15. Nxc4 Nxe4 16. Nfxe5 Nd6 17. Re1 Qf8 {is how the game continued, but the position is winning for White after} 18. Na5 $18 {[%csl Rc7] Big problems with c7 pawn and not only.}) 13. bxc3 e5 {And now e5.} 14. Nc4 {But White is slightly better in many ways.} (14. e4 $6 {is not the same.} Nf6 15. d5 Na5 $132 {[%cal Gb7b6]}) (14. Re1 $5 {is one option.}) 14... e4 15. Nfd2 f5 16. a4 $14 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gc1c2] At some point f3, but also improving moves are fine.}) (10... e5 $2 {was tried in the game Lysyj-Palchun, but it is a mistake.} 11. Nxe5 $1 {We always take with the knight.} (11. dxe5 $2 {Here it is very bad, because after} Ng4 $11 {[%cal Gg4e5] Black is absolutely fine.}) 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Ng4 {Now we can play with} 13. f4 $1 Qc5 14. Re1 Rd8 15. Na3 Be6 16. Rac1 $18 {White's position is winning,}) (10... b5 $2 {Not good, because of} 11. Ne5 $16) (10... Ne4 $2 {We are always happy to see this, because the knight is misplaced.} 11. Qxc4 {And e5 is not a problem anymore.} e5 $2 12. Nxe5 $18 {[%csl Re4]}) (10... Re8 $146 {[%cal Ge6e5] It has never been tried, but a serious move, Black wants e5.} 11. Ne5 $1 {[%csl Re8] The rook on e8 was useful for e5, that's why we stop it, and the rook becomes not so great.} (11. Na3 $6 {Black is anyway doing great after} e5 $1 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. Qxe5 Rxe5 15. Nxc4 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Gc4a5] White's idea is Na5.} Rc5 {[%csl Ra5] But the rook can stay on the 5th rank.} (15... Re7 {After a passive move,} 16. Na5 $14 {White has an advantage.}) 16. b3 Rb8 $11 {[%cal Gc8e6] Very close to full equality.}) (11. Qxc4 $6 e5 $11) 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 {White can't recapture on e5 immediately.} (12... Nd5 $6 {is not great.} 13. Qxc4 c6 {Black can play like this, but it is too passive.} 14. Rd1 Qc7 15. e4 Nb6 16. Qc5 {is one option.} (16. Qc3 {also possible.} Nd7 17. f4 b6 18. Na3 Bb7 19. Nc4 $16) 16... Nd7 17. Qd6 Qxd6 18. exd6 e5 19. Nd2 $16 {Just a better endgame.}) 13. Nd2 Rb8 {Best move for engine.} 14. Nxc4 b6 {[%cal Gc8a6]} (14... b5 $4 {Huge mistake.} 15. Na5 $18 {[%csl Ga5] The knight is too strong.}) 15. Rfd1 Ba6 16. f4 {You can defend e5 pawn.} (16. Bc6 $5 {also possible.} Red8 17. Na3 Nf8 18. b4 Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Rd8 20. Rd4 Rxd4 21. exd4 $14 {Looks interesting as well.}) 16... Red8 17. Na3 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5]} Nf8 (17... c5 {too early.} 18. Rd6 $16 {And you take the d file.}) 18. Bc6 {To stop c5.} Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Rd8 20. Rd4 Rxd4 21. Qxd4 $14 {Some pressure exists.}) 11. Qxc4 {The pawn must be captured.} (11. Na3 $2 {is bad now.} b5 $17) 11... e5 {And now e5, after the queen was provoked to c4.} 12. d5 $5 {is our only chance to fight for something.} (12. dxe5 {Taking on e5 is nothing now.} Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 {This was the game Ragger-Moiseenko, and it soon ended in a draw.} 14. Nc3 c6 $11 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga7a5] Black is doing fine.}) 12... e4 $1 $146 {[%cal Gc6e5] A very strong novelty. The idea is to give an extra square for the c6 knight.} (12... Nd8 $6 {In the email game, Ottesen-Zhekov, Black played this very passive move.} 13. Rd1 $16 {[%csl Rd8] The knight is clearly misplaced.}) 13. dxc6 $5 {I believe, this move is more critical.} (13. Nfd2 {Still, this can be tried.} Ne5 14. Qd4 Rd8 {Engine line:} 15. Nc3 Nc6 16. Qa4 Nxd5 17. Ndxe4 $36 {Almost equal, but still playable.}) 13... exf3 14. Bxf3 bxc6 15. b3 {The material is equal, but in the long term it's very easy to be better with White because of Black's weak structure.} h5 $1 {is the best move for the engine, but it's not an easy move.} (15... Rd8 $6 {If somebody plays this normal move, after} 16. Nc3 $14 {It is already +0.50.}) (15... Ng4 $5 {is one engine recommendation.} 16. Qc2 {Useful move.} (16. Bxg4 {is met with} Rb4 $1 17. Qxc6 Bb7 $1 {Black's idea.} 18. Qc3 Rxg4 19. Nd2 h5 $44 {Black has compensation, quite a nice idea.}) 16... Ne5 17. Be2 Bh3 18. Rd1 $14 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4,Gb1c3,Gc3a4] +0.20, but I think playable for White.}) (15... c5 {is too slow.} 16. Rc1 Nd7 17. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Gc4c3,Gd2c4,Gf3g2] Big advantage.}) 16. Rd1 {Useful move.} Bg4 17. Bxg4 Nxg4 18. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4,Yb1c3,Yc3a4] White has long term prospects, and Black still needs to find difficult moves.} *

