{[%evp 0,27,24,24,25,10,19,19,28,27,56,35,23,27,42,33,39,36,59,13,32,-10,22,32,37,23,56,59,22,24]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. g3 O-O (5... Ne4 {important to know how to react against it.} 6. Bg2 Nxd2 7. Nfxd2 $1 {[%csl Gb1] we keep a knight on b1 so that it could eventually go to c3.} (7. Nbxd2 $6 {would be not precise.} O-O 8. O-O Bxd2 $1 (8... d6 $2 9. Nb3 $1 $18 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ga2a3]}) 9. Qxd2 d6 $132 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ge6e5,Ga7a5] We don't have an important for this structure knight on c3.}) 7... O-O 8. O-O Bxd2 (8... d6 $2 {typical mistake.} 9. Nb3 $18 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ga2a3]}) 9. Qxd2 $1 {[%csl Gb1][%cal Gb1c3] our knight from b1 will go to c3.} d6 {[%csl Gb1]} 10. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Gc3]}) (5... Bxd2+ {doesn't have independent value.} 6. Qxd2 Nc6 (6... d5 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O Rd8 {transposes in Chapter 6.}) (6... d6 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O e5 9. Nc3 {transposes in Chapter 5.}) 7. e3 {transposes in Chapters 2-3.}) 6. Bg2 d5 {the most important independent line.} (6... Nc6 7. e3 {transposes in Chapters 2-3.}) (6... Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 $1 {[%csl Gb1][%cal Gb1c3,Yd7d6] important to have Nc3 option.} (7. Nbxd2 $6 d6 $11 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Ge6e5] Nd2 is misplaced in the d6-e5 structure.}) 7... Ne4 {critical independent line.} (7... d6 8. Nc3 e5 9. O-O {[%csl Gc3] transposes in Chapter 5.}) (7... d5 8. O-O {Transposes in Chapter 6.}) 8. Qc2 Qb4+ 9. Nbd2 Nxd2 10. Nxd2 {[%csl Rb4] Black's problem is that Qb4 is often misplaced.} Qe7 (10... Nc6 11. d5 $1 $146 {has never been played, but it guarantees White a good advantage.} Nd4 (11... Ne5 12. O-O d6 13. Rac1 $16) 12. Qd3 Nf5 (12... Qxb2 $4 {loses immediately.} 13. Rb1 Nc2+ 14. Kd1 $18 {[%cal Gd3c2]}) 13. b3 $16 {It's a good advantage thanks to the extra space and Black's bad pieces (all of them, actually).}) 11. O-O d6 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Ge6e5] This position is important because we know that usually, our knight on d2 is bad in this structure, but here, we have an exception.} 12. b4 $1 e5 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Qc3 $14 {[%cal Gc4c5,Ge2e3,Gd2c4] c5-Nc4-e3 next.}) 7. O-O dxc4 {only 60 games, but it's important.} (7... Nc6 8. a3 $1 Bxd2 9. Nbxd2 {[%csl Gd2,Yd5] Nd2 is good in d5 structures.} Rd8 10. e3 $1 $14 {[%cal Gd1c2] we protect d4, and will continue with Qc2 next with a pleasant advantage.} (10. Qc2 $6 dxc4 $1 $11 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Rd2c4,Gc6d4]})) (7... c6 {too passive:} 8. Qc2 Nbd7 9. Bxb4 $1 Qxb4 {[%csl Rb4]} 10. Nbd2 $16 {[%csl Rb4,Rc8][%cal Gf1e1,Ga2a3,Ge2e4] Qb4 is misplaced. We can continue with Rfe1, and at some moment a3 followed by e2-e4.}) 8. Qc2 {Now, Black has tried many moves.} Nc6 $1 {critical move.} (8... Nbd7 $6 {too passive.} 9. Qxc4 Bd6 10. Qc2 $1 e5 11. Nc3 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4] e4 next.}) (8... c5 9. Bxb4 cxb4 10. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Rc8,Gg2] Typical Catalan-style advantage.}) (8... b5 $2 9. a4 $1 $16 {[%csl Rb5] Black cannot hold the queenside.}) (8... Bxd2 9. Nbxd2 {[%cal Gd2c4,Re6e5]} b5 {and now we will play for Catalan-style compensation:} 10. Ne5 Nd5 11. b3 cxb3 12. Nxb3 $44 {[%cal Gf1c1,Gb3c5] Rfc1-Nc5 next. Every Catalan player would love this position.}) 9. Rd1 $1 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Gd1d4] Important to have d4 defended, and sometimes we will play Rxd2.} (9. Qxc4 $6 {not precise because it allows} Bxd2 10. Nbxd2 Rd8 $1 11. Rac1 e5 $11 {and Black equalizes.}) 9... Bd6 {the most challenging move.} (9... e5 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxd2 12. Nxd2 Qxe5 13. Nxc4 Qe7 14. e4 $14 {typical pleasant position.}) (9... Rd8 10. Qxc4 Bxd2 11. Rxd2 $1 {big difference compared to the 9.Qxc4 line.} e5 {[%csl Gd2] and now, thanks to the rook on d2, we can play} 12. d5 Nb8 13. e4 $14) 10. Na3 $1 $146 {[%cal Ga3c4] I believe that this is White's strongest and most ambitious continuation.} (10. Qxc4 {possible, but we will not have too much:} e5 11. dxe5 (11. d5 Nd4 $1 $11 {strong concrete move.}) 11... Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 (12... Bxe5 $2 13. Bb4 $16) 13. Bc3 Qf5 14. Nd2 Re8 $14 {more pleasant for White, but nothing special.}) 10... Bxa3 {if not Bxa3, we will just play Nxc4.} 11. bxa3 Qxa3 {critical.} (11... e5 {if Black doesn't accept the pawn, we will have a pleasant position after} 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. Qxc4 $36 {[%csl Gd2,Gg2] two nice bishops and a lot of play on the queenside.}) 12. Qxc4 {[%cal Gf3e5] our idea is Ne5, and Black should be precise.} Bd7 $1 {most accurate defense.} (12... h6 13. Ne5 $1 $16) (12... Rd8 13. Bg5 $16) 13. Rab1 $5 (13. Ne5 $6 {now, this is not good:} Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd5 $11 {[%cal Gd7c6]}) 13... Rab8 14. Qc2 $44 {[%cal Ge2e4] e4 next, and we have a very good, and for sure full, compensation. If you are not ready to play without a pawn, you can always go for 10.Qxc4, but if you want to be ambitious, 10.Na3 is definitely the way.} *

