{[%evp 0,35,24,24,24,14,9,6,40,40,40,36,37,3,19,14,22,19,10,10,27,22,14,32,21,16,27,31,31,31,31,31,47,47,52,26,17,43]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Bxd2+ {The most solid line for Black.} 5. Qxd2 (5. Nbxd2 $6 {We don't take with the knight, because after} O-O $132 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Gd7d6,Gd8e7,Ge6e5] Black will play with d6-e5 and the knight is misplaced.}) 5... O-O 6. g3 d6 (6... b6 {transposes to the Queen's Indian, which is the topic of the next database.}) 7. Bg2 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gd8e7] This is similar to Chapter 3, but Black didn't play yet Nc6 or Qe7. So, probably Black will choose one of the two, because if both moves happen on the board, we can simply transpose to Chapter 3.} Qe7 (7... Nc6 8. Nc3 e5 {This is Black's idea.} (8... Qe7 {We can transpose to Chapter 3.} 9. O-O e5 10. e3 {Transposition.}) 9. O-O {Thanks to saving a tempo on Qe7, Black will play with} (9. h3 $5 {is also possible, doesn't ruin anything.} Qe7 (9... e4 $2 10. Ng5 $16 {Just wins a pawn.}) 10. O-O {[%csl Gh3][%cal Ge2e3] We have h3 instead of e3, just a normal version.} e4 {Critical move.} 11. Ng5 Bf5 {And maybe that e3 is not played is even good for White.} 12. d5 {forced line begins:} Ne5 13. Ngxe4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Bxe4 f5 16. Bg2 Nxc4 17. Qc2 $36 {With play on the c-file.}) 9... Bg4 {[%csl Yd8] A serious move.} (9... Qe7 {transposes to Chapter 3.} 10. e3 {Not necessary, but the easiest.}) 10. e3 {is in the spirit of Chapter 3.} (10. d5 {The most common move, but I don't like it because} Ne7 $1 {[%csl Ge7] Black has the nice square for the knight.} 11. e4 Qd7 $132 {[%cal Gg4h3,Ge7g6] All in all, Black has a very normal position.}) (10. h3 {We have some problems with the d4 pawn.} Bxf3 11. Bxf3 exd4 $13 {And it's not easy to find something for White here.}) (10. Rad1 $5 {An interesting move, trying to play an improved version of 10.h3.} Bxf3 11. Bxf3 exd4 (11... Nxd4 $6 {is bad, because} 12. Bxb7 Rb8 13. Bg2 $16 {White has the strong bishop.}) 12. Nb5 {And Rad1 is more useful than h3.} Ne5 {is probably the best.} (12... Qd7 $6 {doesn't come with tempo against h3.} 13. Nxd4 $14 {Just slightly better for White.}) 13. Nxd4 Nxf3+ {And now how to take on f3?} (13... Nxc4 $6 {is bad again.} 14. Qc3 Ne5 15. Bxb7 Rb8 16. Bg2 $16) 14. exf3 $5 {With the pawn is the most interesting.} (14. Nxf3 {is nothing.} Re8 $11 {No problem for Black.}) 14... Qd7 15. Kg2 Rfe8 16. b4 {The position is slightly better for White.} Re5 17. Qc3 Rae8 18. Rd2 $14 {[%csl Re3,Re4,Gf2,Gf3][%cal Gd4c2,Gc2e3,Gf1d1] White can play a long game here.}) (10. dxe5 {is also a possible option.} Nxe5 {The pawn on b7 is not hanging for now.} (10... dxe5 11. Qe3 {[%csl Re5] Pressure against the pawn.} Qe7 (11... Re8 $6 {runs into} 12. Rfd1 {with tempo.} Qc8 13. Nd5 {is fantastic for White.} Nxd5 14. cxd5 $14 {Pressure on the c-file.}) 12. Rfd1 Rad8 13. Nd5 Qd6 {Already tough move to play.} 14. Rd2 $14 {White is slightly better.}) 11. b3 $5 {is more interesting.} (11. Nxe5 {leads to nothing.} dxe5 12. Qxd8 Rfxd8 13. Bxb7 Rab8 {And b2 drops.} 14. Rfd1 Rxd1+ 15. Rxd1 Kf8 $11) 11... Nxf3+ 12. exf3 Bd7 13. f4 Bc6 14. Nd5 $14 {More pleasant position.}) 10... Re8 (10... Qe7 11. b3 {transposes to Chapter 3.}) 11. h3 {We can play h3 now since no problems with the d4 pawn.} Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Qd7 13. Bg2 exd4 14. exd4 Rad8 {Normal moves so far.} 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. cxd5 Ne7 17. Rac1 $14 {[%cal Gc1c3,Gf1c1,Yd8c8,Yg1h2,Yh3h4,Yg2h3] Risk free position for White, pressure exists.}) 8. Nc3 e5 (8... c5 $2 {Just bad.} 9. dxc5 $1 dxc5 10. Ne5 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rb8c6] Strong move.} (10. O-O {don't play just castle, because} Nc6 $14 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gd2e3] Black's position is not so bad.}) 10... Nbd7 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. O-O-O Qxd2+ 13. Rxd2 $16 {[%cal Gc3b5,Gb5d6,Ya7a6,Gc3a4] Better endgame.}) 9. O-O {[%cal Gc8g4,Gf8e8,Gc7c6] Now Black can play without Nc6:} Re8 {The main move.} (9... c6 $6 {is the worst move for concrete reasons:} 10. c5 $1 {[%csl Rd6,Re5] Undermining Black's structure.} exd4 (10... dxc5 $2 {is just nightmare position for Black.} 11. dxe5 Nfd7 12. Qf4 $16 {No development.}) 11. cxd6 Qxd6 12. Nxd4 {And White has a very big development advantage. For example, if both sides play normal moves:} Rd8 13. Rad1 Na6 14. Qc1 Qe7 15. Rd2 Nc7 16. Rfd1 {And Black is feeling the pressure.} Bd7 {Best move probably.} (16... g6 $4 {loses to} 17. Nxc6 $18) 17. h3 $16 {with e4 idea.} (17. Na4 $16 {with Nc5 idea.})) (9... Bg4 {White has more than one good option.} 10. h3 $5 {is interesting.} (10. Ne1 {is also a good move.} exd4 (10... c6 $6 {is also not good.} 11. Nc2 $16 {[%csl Gc2,Yf3] The knight on c2 stays well. The bishop on g4 does nothing now.}) (10... Nc6 $6 {is met with} 11. Nd5 $1 {Strong resource.} Nxd5 12. cxd5 Nxd4 {looks like Black won a pawn, but after} 13. e3 $1 {Black is losing material.} Nb5 (13... Nf5 14. f3 $18 {[%csl Rf5]}) 14. a4 $18 {[%csl Rb5]}) 11. Qxd4 Nc6 12. Qd2 Rfe8 13. e4 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb2b3,Gf2f3,Ge1c2,Gc2e3] It is clear that White has some pressure.}) 10... Bxf3 (10... Bh5 $6 11. Nh4 $1 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Rf5,Gh4] is the idea.}) 11. exf3 $5 {Typical recapture.} (11. Bxf3 $6 {Taking with the bishop is not too much.} Nc6 $132) 11... Nc6 12. d5 Nd4 13. f4 $1 {This is definitely something for White.} c5 14. dxc6 bxc6 15. Rfe1 $36 {With a lot of pressure.}) (9... Nc6 10. e3 {Transposes to Chapter 3.}) 10. h3 {Against Bg4, is also interesting.} (10. e3 {In this case, the rook on e8 is more useful than the knight on c6, and it can be seen in the line:} e4 11. Ng5 Bf5 12. f3 exf3 13. Rxf3 Bg6 14. Raf1 {And now} Nbd7 $1 $11 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Yd7f6] Big difference.}) (10. Ne1 {[%cal Ge1c2] is a good move, with the idea to bring the knight to c2.} exd4 (10... e4 {is another story, because the pawn is on e2 not on e3.} 11. Nc2 $16 {[%csl Ye2,Ge3][%cal Gc2e3,Gf2f3] Positionally better for White.}) 11. Qxd4 $14 {[%cal Ge1c2,Ga1d1] Pressure and small advantage.}) 10... e4 {It's good for White after} (10... Nc6 {If Nc6 we can transpose or play something else.} 11. e3 {Transposes to Chapter 3.} (11. e4 {A lot of good moves for White.})) 11. Ng5 Bf5 (11... e3 $6 {is bad for many reasons.} 12. Qxe3 {White can play dynamically.} (12. Qd3 $5 $14 {is also good enough for an advantage.}) 12... Qxe3 13. fxe3 Rxe3 14. Rxf6 $1 {Temporary sacrifice.} gxf6 15. Nge4 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gg1f2] The rook is trapped, and the best for Black is something like:} Nc6 16. Kf2 Rxe4 17. Nxe4 Nxd4 18. Nxf6+ $16 {But of course, the endgame is by far not equal.}) 12. g4 $1 {New ideas thanks to the pawn on h3.} Bg6 13. f4 exf3 14. exf3 {Easy play.} h6 15. Rae1 Qd8 16. Rxe8+ Qxe8 17. f4 $1 {Strong resource.} hxg5 18. Bxb7 $16 {[%csl Ra8] is the idea.} *

