{[%evp 0,82,29,30,30,6,6,6,36,44,41,33,21,-2,10,10,10,10,24,18,49,54,57,-16,9,46,18,18,-3,-4,35,31,22,22,22,22,21,27,16,-8,-1,-1,64,0,59,16,69,69,77,58,91,60,118,99,139,84,127,99,84,98,96,94,97,100,98,31,49,33,85,71,25,35,63,18,33,26,-6,0,109,139,163,259,263,317,347]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 d5 (5... O-O {leads to the same.} 6. g3 d5 {Transposition.}) 6. g3 O-O 7. Bg2 {[%cal Yc7c6,Yb8d7] Black has a choice, but the most important line involves both the moves Nbd7 and c6.} c6 (7... b6 $6 {Without c6 is a bad structure after} 8. cxd5 $1 exd5 9. Nc3 $14 {[%csl Gb6,Yd5][%cal Gc7c6] Black had to retake with e-pawn, and we are happy with this structure.}) (7... Nbd7 {If Black plays this with the idea of dxc4, be aware of a famous trick:} 8. O-O dxc4 {Very important:} 9. Rc1 $1 {is the best, and I played it against a FM from Germany in GRENKE 2019.} (9. Na3 $6 {Don't play this, because of} e5 $1 10. dxe5 Nxe5 $1 {Important trick.} 11. Qxd8 Nxf3+ $11 {And Black is fine, I also ''fell'' for this trick, but I was aware and I was fine with making a draw, because I was leading the tournament, in Basso-Gonda, 2018.}) 9... c5 {was played in the game Giri-Zontakh, but we can play the typical Catalan structure:} (9... c6 {My opponent's choice.} 10. Rxc4 Qe7 {I played b4, which I probably confused with another position, but} 11. b3 $5 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gd2b2,Gb1d2] was more precise.} e5 {If Black plays e5, now we can take:} 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. Nc3 Be6 15. Rd4 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1,Ge2e4,Gf2f4,Gh2h3] Easy plan for White, Black definitely didn't equalize.}) (9... Rb8 $146 {is engine's recommendation, with the idea of b6-Bb7. Very deep idea.} 10. Rxc4 b6 11. Na3 Bb7 {Black needs to make sure that the concrete} 12. Nb5 {is not working because of} (12. Rac1 $5 {But we can simply double the rooks.} c5 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Rd4 {And a typical position arises after} Qe7 15. Ne5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 $14 {[%csl Gc6] Not a winning advantage, but +0.40 we have.}) 12... c5 $1 $11 {Very strong.}) 10. dxc5 Nxc5 {[%csl Rc8,Gg2] Big difference between the bishops.} 11. Ne5 $14 {White is clearly doing better.}) (7... Qe7 {is a possible system, with the point of developing the rook to d8.} 8. O-O Rd8 9. Rc1 Nc6 $5 {This is Black's idea.} (9... c6 {is just passive.} 10. Qf4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 {And the rook on d8 makes no sense, since the plan is to push e6-e5.} b6 $6 {is bad, because of} 12. Qc7 $1 $14 {Concrete problems.}) 10. e3 {[%csl Rc6,Yd4] My suggestion, to make the knight on c6 feel useless.} a5 {is the best, just to take some space on the queenside. But now White has a lot of playable moves:} (10... Bd7 {is too slow.} 11. Qc3 Be8 12. Nbd2 $16 {Black has no e5.}) (10... dxc4 $2 {And very important to remember that this is no trouble for White, because after} 11. Rxc4 e5 {Logical plan.} 12. Rxc6 $1 {is very important.} bxc6 13. Nxe5 $18 {This is not compensation, but just winning for White.}) 11. Qe1 $5 {Interesting, and against e5 it is more useful than Qe2.} (11. Qe2 {also possible, and the most important is that dxc4 and e5 is no trouble for us.} e5 {is met with} 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Rxc6 $1 bxc6 14. Nxe5 $36 {Typical reaction.}) (11. Qc2 {also possible.}) (11. Na3 $5 {is interesting.}) 11... a4 (11... e5 {Because here after} 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Rxc6 bxc6 14. Nxe5 Ra6 15. Nc3 $36 {[%cal Ge1c3] And the queen supports the knight on c3.}) 12. Na3 $36 {Just playable position, Black is not equalizing by force.}) 8. O-O Nbd7 {The most important position of this variation.} (8... dxc4 {If Black takes now, we can play for Catalan-style compensation after} 9. Ne5 b5 {Critical move.} (9... Nbd7 $6 {is just positionally bad.} 10. Nxc4 $14) 10. b3 $1 {And we play for compensation.} (10. Nxc6 $2 {is even preferable for Black after} Nxc6 11. Bxc6 Rb8 $36) 10... cxb3 11. axb3 Bb7 12. Nc3 Nbd7 {is best by the engine.} (12... a6 13. Rfc1 $36 {Just typical compensation.}) 13. Rfd1 {was played in the game Fressinet-Macovei, 2023.} Qb6 (13... Nxe5 $6 {After} 14. dxe5 $14 {[%csl Yc5,Yd6][%cal Gc3e4,Ye4c5,Ye4d6] Our knight will go to the d6-c5 squares.}) 14. Nxd7 $1 {was the best.} (14. b4 $6 {was played, but now Nxe5 was good.} Nxe5 $1 $146 {is good now, because after} 15. dxe5 Rfd8 $1 {Black has this tempo.} 16. Qb2 Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Nd5 18. Ne4 a5 $132 {Black can free up his position.}) 14... Nxd7 15. b4 {[%cal Gc3e4,Ge4c5] And Black's position is locked down.} Rfd8 {Normal move.} (15... a5 $2 {fails to} 16. bxa5 $16 {[%cal Ra8a5,Gc3d5] Black cannot recapture the pawn.}) 16. Ne4 Qc7 17. Qf4 $5 {is an additional idea.} Qxf4 18. gxf4 $14 {White has a dominant position.}) 9. Rc1 {My recommendation. We defend the c4 pawn with the rook.} (9. Qc2 {is the second most common move, but after all White is losing a tempo.} b6 10. Nbd2 {It's playable, but also Black is fine, for example:} Bb7 11. e4 {The most logical plan.} dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Rb8 $1 $11 {[%cal Gc6c5] c5 next and Black has no problems.}) 9... b6 {The most logical and the main line.} (9... Qe7 {With similar ideas to 9...Re8.} 10. Qe3 {is my recommendation now, since it doesn't stay under the rook's vision.} (10. Qf4 {is also possible, but against Qe7, I think the queen on e3 is more solid.}) 10... dxc4 (10... b6 {was played in the game Gukesh-Abdusattorov, Tata Steel 2023.} 11. Ne5 Bb7 12. Qa3 $5 $146 {We can play Qa3 immediately.} (12. cxd5 {Gukesh's choice, but I don't like it, because after} Nxd5 $1 {Black was doing fine.} 13. Qa3 Nxe5 14. Qxe7 Nxe7 15. dxe5 Rad8 $11 {Equal position, the game ended in a draw.}) 12... Qxa3 13. Nxa3 Nxe5 14. dxe5 {But it is not the same as the Gukesh game.} Ng4 (14... Nd7 {is not great.} 15. cxd5 $1 $14 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gc1c7,Rc6d5] Tactical problem for Black.}) 15. f4 f6 {Logical move.} 16. Bf3 {And the game continues with something like:} Ne3 17. exf6 Rxf6 18. Rc3 Nf5 (18... d4 19. Rd3 Rd8 20. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Gc4c5] The d4 pawn looks a bit vulnerable.}) 19. Nc2 $14 {Long game ahead, definitely slightly better endgame.}) (10... Re8 {We will transpose to 9...Re8, after} 11. Nbd2 e5 {The most logical, and we enter the endgame:} 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. Qxe5 Rxe5 15. cxd5 {See under 9...Re8.}) 11. Rxc4 Nd5 {was seen in the game Kramnik-Andreikin, 2013.} 12. Qa3 $1 {Good move.} Re8 13. Qxe7 {Kramink took, good decision.} (13. e4 $5 {is maybe more precise, with the idea that after} N5b6 14. Rc2 e5 {We can keep the queens with} (14... Qxa3 {If Black takes, now after} 15. Nxa3 e5 16. Rd1 {We are slightly better developed compared to the Kramnik game.} exd4 17. Nxd4 g6 18. b4 $14 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Gd4b3,Gb3a5] With the idea to reroute the knight to the fantastic a5 square.}) 15. Qe3 $5 exd4 16. Nxd4 $14 {Slightly better for White.}) 13... Rxe7 14. e4 N5b6 15. Rc3 $5 $146 {I think the rook on c3 is more active.} (15. Rc2 {was played in the game, which is also good.} e5 16. Nbd2 a5 $13 {Kramnik lost in the end, but probably because he overpushed, White's position is playable, with pressure.}) 15... e5 16. a4 $36 {White is definitely pressing.}) (9... Re8 {[%cal Gd5c4,Gc1c4,Ge6e5] with the idea to take on c4 and play e5.} 10. Qf4 {I like this move, to prevent e5.} (10. Qe3 $2 {is a bad move, because it doesn't stop e5.} dxc4 11. Rxc4 e5 $1 {Anyways.} 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Rxe5 $1 {Strong move.} 14. Qxe5 Qd1+ 15. Bf1 Bh3 16. Nd2 Qxa1 $17 {Black is better.}) (10. Ne5 $6 {is not good, when Black's structure is compact, it works well when dxc4 is played.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7 {And Black's position is fantastic.} 12. cxd5 $6 exd5 $1 13. f4 f6 $17 {Big advantage for Black.}) 10... Qe7 {[%cal Gd5c4,Gc1c4,Ge6e5] Logical move, Black insists on the e5 plan.} (10... dxc4 {makes no sense now.} 11. Rxc4 $14 {No e5.}) (10... b6 11. Nbd2 {If Black plays b6 now, we can just develop:} Bb7 12. e4 {Logical plan, and after} dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 {The difference now is that} Rb8 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Gc6c5] can be met with} 15. c5 $1 $16 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gb2b4,Gf3e5] Because the rook is already on c1.}) 11. Nbd2 e5 {Logical move.} (11... dxc4 $2 {is bad.} 12. Nxc4 $16 {No e5 anymore.}) (11... Nf8 {with idea Ng6 can be met with} 12. Ne5 {It is good now, because Black lost some tempi.} Ng6 13. Qe3 Nxe5 {We are in full control after} 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. f4 f6 16. Nf3 $16 {White is better.}) 12. dxe5 {Now a lot of exchanges:} Nxe5 13. Nxe5 (13. cxd5 {is playable, but allows the extra option of} Ng6 $5 14. Qd4 Nxd5 15. e4 $14 {[%eval 25,0]}) 13... Qxe5 14. Qxe5 Rxe5 15. cxd5 Nxd5 {is the most common continuation.} (15... Rxe2 {can be met with} 16. dxc6 $1 {Intermediate move.} Rxd2 17. cxb7 {And Black didn't fully equalize after} Bxb7 18. Bxb7 Rb8 19. b3 $1 $14 {Important to save the b2 pawn, and White can put pressure over the board.}) 16. e4 $1 {[%cal Gd2c4] Strong move, Nc4 next is our idea.} Nb6 {Logical.} 17. f4 {Grab some space.} (17. Nc4 $6 {Don't play this, because we don't want to exchange the knights.} Nxc4 18. Rxc4 $11 {Position is just equal.}) 17... Re7 18. Nb3 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gb3c5] The knight is headed to c5.} (18. a4 {was played in the game Karpov-Andersson, but I am not a big fan of the a4-a5 inclusion.} a5 19. Nb3 {I understand that the a5 pawn is potentially hanging, but so is the a4 pawn.} f6 {was Ulf's choice, but in a couple of moves, Black got seriously outplayed after} (19... g6 {was maybe the best with the point of} 20. Rc5 Be6 $132 {[%cal Ge6c4,Rb3d4] Counterplay.}) 20. Ra3 {The rook will join the game via the 3rd rank.} Be6 21. Nc5 Bf7 22. Rd3 {Control the d-file.} Rae8 23. Bh3 $1 {Strong move.} Nc8 24. Bd7 $1 Rd8 25. Rcd1 Nb6 26. Bg4 Rxd3 27. Rxd3 {And suddenly Black's position is close to being lost.} Kf8 28. Rd8+ Re8 29. Rd4 Rb8 30. Rd7 $1 {Strong move, and final trick.} h5 31. Bh3 Ke8 32. Rc7 $18 {And it was just game over. Karpov-Andersson, 1-0, Olympiad 1988.}) 18... Kf8 19. Rc2 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gb3c5] Playable endgame, slightly better.}) (9... dxc4 {If they start with dxc4, after} 10. Rxc4 Re8 {with the idea of e5.} 11. Ne5 {becomes stronger, and it transposes to another position.}) 10. Ne5 {I recommend to start with this move. Now Black has two options:} (10. cxd5 {is a serious option and the main line.} cxd5 11. Nc3 Ba6 {But I think that Black is doing more or less fine. I tried to analyze:} 12. a4 Rc8 13. Nb5 {has been seen in some high-level games, but I think it is just equality:} Rxc1+ 14. Rxc1 Qa8 {is good enough.} 15. Rc7 {seems like White has some small pressure, but after} (15. Nc7 {If you take the pair of bishops, same story:} Qb7 16. Nxa6 Qxa6 17. Qc2 b5 $11 {Just equal.}) 15... Bxb5 16. axb5 Rc8 {Black neutralizes and it is just equal.} 17. Qc3 Rxc7 18. Qxc7 Qb8 19. Qc6 Nf8 $11 {[%cal Gf8g6,Gg6e7] Ng6-Ne7 next. 10.cxd5 is a too conservative approach, in my opinion.}) (10. b4 {has been tried in some games, but Black can play immediately} a5 {To ask a question to our previous move.} 11. b5 {is the idea, but} cxb5 12. cxb5 Bb7 {I am not sure that this inclusion is not bad for Black. It is more difficult to create something.} 13. Nc3 Qe7 14. Na4 Qb4 $11 {Just equal.}) 10... Bb7 {The best move.} (10... Nxe5 $2 {is critical to check for understanding the strength of 10.Ne5. But I think it's a positional mistake for Black:} 11. dxe5 Nd7 12. cxd5 {You can also start with f4, but this is easier.} cxd5 13. f4 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gb1c3,Gc3b5,Gb5d4] And White is slightly better, because we have a clear plan of improving the knight to d4.} Bb7 {And now one idea to keep in mind is:} (13... f6 $2 {is a mistake, because of} 14. Bxd5 $1 $16 {[%csl Ra8,Rg8][%cal Gd2d5,Gd5g8,Gd5a8] Typical tactic.}) 14. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c2,Ga3b5,Gc2d4] The knight is guaranteed to get to d4.} (14. Nc3 {is possible, but Black can play} a6 {to stop Nb5.} 15. e3 {The knight goes to e2-d4.} a5 {But Black can organize some counterplay against the d3 square.} 16. Nb5 Nc5 17. Nd4 Ba6 $132 {White is still preferable here, but there is an alternative way.}) 14... a6 {Probably Black should stop Nb5.} (14... f6 $2 {is a mistake, because of} 15. Nb5 $1 fxe5 16. Nc7 $18) 15. Nc2 Rc8 (15... f6 {is met with} 16. Nd4 $16 {And Black has concrete problems.}) 16. Nd4 Qe7 {Logical way to play.} 17. a3 {Good move, played in the game Georgiev-Antic, 2012.} Rfd8 18. Qe3 $5 $146 {And it's not easy to play with Black.} (18. e3 {was played in the game, but I don't like it. There is no need to rush with it.} Nc5 19. Qb4 Qc7 20. Bf1 {is how the game continued.} a5 21. Qe1 a4 22. Qb4 $14 {[%cal Gf1b5,Gc1c3,Ga1c1] In the end, White won, slightly better position, easy play.}) 18... h6 {Engine suggestion, but we can continue with} (18... Nc5 $6 {can be met with} 19. f5 $1 $40 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge2e5] And the e5 pawn is not hanging.}) 19. Rf1 {Attacking move.} Rc7 20. Rad1 Rdc8 {Black takes the c-file, but} 21. g4 $1 $40 {Really good chances for an attack.} Nb8 {[%cal Gb8c6] is a logical plan, but fails after} 22. f5 Nc6 23. fxe6 {Tactical sequence.} fxe6 24. Nxe6 $18) 11. cxd5 {Anyway we need to play cxd5 at some moment, so I suggest to do it now.} (11. Nc3 Qe7 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Rc2) 11... cxd5 {The main move, and now White has a choice:} (11... Nxe5 {And now important:} 12. dxc6 $1 {Intermezzo.} (12. dxe5 $6 {is almost nothing.} Nxd5 13. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c4,Gc4d6] The idea is simple, but} b5 $1 {is strong.} 14. Nc2 c5 $13 {Not easy to fight for advantage.}) 12... Nxc6 {was seen in the game Polak-Shengelia, 2023.} 13. Bxc6 Bxc6 14. Rxc6 {The evaluation is +0,40 not +1, so it means that Black has some compensation.} Qd7 15. Rc1 {But okay, Black can play with compensation, we can play with the pawn.} Rfd8 {was seen in the game.} (15... Rad8 $1 {is engine recommendation, with the idea.} 16. Rd1 e5 $1 {And after} 17. dxe5 Qc7 18. Qc1 Rxd1+ 19. Qxd1 Ne4 $1 {Black wants to organize counterplay, but it doesn't matter.} 20. Na3 Qc5 21. e3 Qxe5 22. Qe2 $14 {A pawn is a pawn, during the game it doesn't matter if it is +0.40 or +1, we can play it.}) 16. Rd1 Rac8 (16... e5 $6 {is not so great, because after} 17. dxe5 Qc7 18. Qc1 Rxd1+ 19. Qxd1 {Comparing to the other position,} Ne4 20. e6 $1 {is a strong move and the rook on a8 is just worse.} fxe6 21. Nc3 Nxc3 22. bxc3 Qxc3 23. Rc1 $16 {[%csl Rg8] And it's interesting to see, that the evaluation is +1, despite equal material.}) 17. Nc3 e5 18. d5 Rc4 {And now White allowed Rd4, but much stronger was} 19. Qe3 $1 $16 {And the evaluation is +1 already.}) 12. Na3 $5 {is my recommendation. We complete development, where Ne4 is less strong.} (12. Nc3 {is a possible move, but Black has} Ne4 $1 {Even if played only in 1 game, it's very strong.} 13. Nxe4 (13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Qe3 Nf6 $11 {0.00, maybe White has small prospects, but it's almost nothing.}) 13... Nxe5 $1 {is the idea.} (13... dxe4 $6 {Not this, because} 14. Nc6 $14 {White is slightly better.}) 14. Ng5 {is the best.} (14. dxe5 {leads to an equal endgame, it looks like:} dxe4 15. Qxd8 Rfxd8 16. Rc7 Rab8 $11 {Full equality.}) 14... Nc6 15. Nf3 Qd6 $11 {Black exchanged one pair of kngihts, and no problem.}) (12. Nc6 {is no problem for Black, because after} Bxc6 {Black is happy to exchange the bishop for the knight.} 13. Rxc6 Rc8 $11 {[%csl Rg2] The bishop on g2 is not your typical Catalan bishop, because it is a different structure. In an Exchange Slav, the bishop is not fantastic on g2.}) 12... a6 $1 {The best move was played only once out of 6 games, in the game Andreikin-Postny. The idea is to prevent Nb5.} (12... Ne4 {was actually played against me in the Italian Championship 2021, by the IM Gilevich.} 13. Qf4 {[%cal Re4c3] And the knight is a bit strange on e4.} g5 $2 {He played a concrete move, but a huge mistake, because after} (13... Nxe5 {Black had to take.} 14. dxe5 Rc8 15. Nb5 $14 {But this is definitely slightly better for White.}) 14. Qe3 Nxe5 15. dxe5 {[%csl Re4,Rg5] Big problems with both the knight and the pawn.} f5 {[%cal Ga3b5] Now Nb5 was the strongest.} 16. exf6 {was also okay.} Qxf6 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Rc7 $16 {[%csl Rb7,Ge3,Re4,Rg8][%cal Ga3b5] Black is left with only weaknesses.} Bd5 19. Nb5 h6 20. Rac1 $18 {was the strongest, with evaluation of +2.50 already.} (20. Rd1 {I played in the game, and later won.})) (12... Nxe5 {is the same story as 10...Nxe5.} 13. dxe5 Nd7 (13... Ne4 {was seen in 2 games.} 14. Qd4 {is also good now, because the d4 square is available.} (14. Qe3 $5 $146 {is always a good option.}) 14... Rc8 {was played in the game Andreikin-Bogosavljevic, 2021.} (14... a5 {was played in Babula-Tratar, 2024.} 15. Nb5 Nc5 16. Qe3 $16 {And also here White is better.}) 15. b4 $5 $16 {[%csl Gb2,Re4][%cal Gd4b2] The knight on e4 is a bit tricky, because it can be always captured. This is +0.80.}) 14. f4 {We transposed to the game Grischuk-Eljanov, 2010.} a5 15. Nb5 Nc5 16. Rc2 f6 17. Qe3 {With an obvious advantage for White.} fxe5 18. Qxe5 Rf5 19. Qd6 $14 {Grischuk converted the advantage into a full point.}) 13. Nc6 {[%csl Ra6] I think it is a good moment to play it, because we will conquer the c-file, and Black played a6, which could be hanging at some point.} (13. Qb4 {Only applies psychological pressure, but it doesn't lead anywhere.} Rc8 (13... Rb8 $5 {But Black can also be solid.}) 14. Nac4 $5 {You can try to confuse your opponents, but Black can find:} a5 $1 {Good move.} 15. Nxa5 bxa5 16. Qxb7 Rb8 {Engine line.} 17. Qc6 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Ng4 $132 {With counterplay.}) 13... Bxc6 {The most logical.} 14. Rxc6 Rc8 {was played in the game, logical to fight on the c-file.} (14... Qb8 {can be met with} 15. Rac1 {[%cal Rb8b7,Gc6c7] And White is first to take the line.} b5 16. Nc2 Nb6 17. Nb4 Nc4 18. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Gc5,Ge5][%cal Gb4d3,Gb2b3] looks nice for White.}) 15. Rac1 Rxc6 16. Rxc6 Qa8 {is very natural, and was played in the game, but after} (16... Nb8 {is the best for the engine, but still after} 17. Rc1 Qd7 18. Qc2 $1 {We control the c-file.} Ne8 {[%cal Ge8d6] with the idea Nd6, can be met with} (18... h6 19. Nb1 $14 {[%csl Ga3,Ra6][%cal Gb1d2] We can improve the knight, especially since a6 has been played, the knight on a3 was not fantastic.}) 19. e4 $5 {To activate the bishop.} dxe4 20. Qxe4 Nd6 21. Qe5 $36 {[%csl Gg2] And White definitely has the pressure here, somewhere d5 can be annoying for Black. The bishop on g2 is strong.}) 17. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Ga3b1,Gb1d2,Ge2e3,Gg2f3,Gg1g2,Gh2h4] It is not easy to fight against the control on the c-file. For the engine is not so much, +0.20, but in a practical game, it is difficult for Black to just wait. At some moment, Black will collapse and make a mistake, while White has very easy moves.} *

