{[%evp 0,25,16,21,24,6,15,15,23,33,35,42,45,38,39,40,35,25,41,41,37,33,37,26,27,44,52,52]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 a5 (4... Be7 {We will speak more about this in the Informational Chapter, but we can compare some lines between this position and the position with 4...a5 5.a3 Be7:} 5. Nc3 d5 6. Bf4 O-O 7. e3 b6 (7... c5 {is a serious line.} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Qc2 Nc6 10. Rd1 Qa5 $11 {Black's most common move, with big theory.}) (7... Nbd7 {In this case, the knight jump makes no sense.} 8. Nb5 (8. Qc2 {is just equal.} c5 $11) 8... Bb4+ $1 $132 {And White wasted time.}) 8. Qc2 Ba6 9. Nb5 {is not that impressive anymore, because after} Bxb5 10. cxb5 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Ga7a6] Black can challenge the b5 pawn, but also} Bb4+ $1 $132 {is a very annoying check.}) 5. a3 Bxd2+ (5... Be7 $6 {Now this is not a problem for us.} 6. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] White's idea is e4, so Black should play d5.} d5 (6... O-O $6 7. e4 $16) 7. Bf4 {[%csl Ra5,Ye7,Gf4] Now we play a QGD with Bf4, but it is an improved version, because the moves a3 and a5 are played, where the pawn on a5 is misplaced.} O-O 8. e3 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc7c5,Gb7b6] In the main position, Black usually has 3 moves.} b6 {The modern approach is for sure not good.} (8... c5 {Also here the difference is quite huge.} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Qc2 Nc6 11. Rd1 $16 {[%cal Rd8a5,Ga7a6,Gb7b5] There is no Qa5 comparing to the main position, just terrible position for Black.}) (8... Nbd7 {If this, we can jump with} 9. Nb5 {to attack c7.} (9. Qc2 {This is also a better version, because after} c5 10. Rd1 $14 {The b5 square is a serious weakness, comparing to 4...Be7.}) 9... Ne8 10. Qc2 c6 11. Nc3 Nef6 12. cxd5 {leads to pleasant positions.} Nxd5 (12... exd5 13. Bd3 $14 {Carlsbad with a3-a5 is a good version for White, a5 is a weakness.}) (12... cxd5 $6 {In the Slav, the b5 square is a big weakness now.} 13. Bd3 $16 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gc3b5]}) 13. Bg3 $14) 9. Qc2 Ba6 10. Nb5 $1 {Good move.} Bxb5 11. cxb5 $16 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Re7b4,Ra7a6] Comparing to 4...Be7, the position is fantastic for White, no way to challenge the b5 pawn, no check on b4. Big advantage for White.}) 6. Qxd2 {[%csl Ga3,Ra5] The inclusion of the moves a3-a5 will favor White at some point (the a5 pawn is weak and also the b5 square). Let's see some examples:} O-O (6... b6 {is one of the critical tries.} 7. Nc3 Bb7 8. e3 $5 {is a safe move.} (8. Qc2 {[%cal Ge2e4] This is how I used to play this line, and I won 2 nice games with it, both in the last round.} d5 {has to be played.} (8... O-O $6 {GM Kosic allowed me to play e4, but that is not a good idea.} 9. e4 d6 10. Bd3 (10. O-O-O $1 {was even stronger, but I was not aware of this concept 5 years ago.}) 10... h6 11. Rd1 (11. O-O-O $1 $16 {[%cal Gh1g1,Gg2g4,Gg4g5] Again, this was just crushing.}) 11... Qe7 12. O-O {The position is still better for White.} Nbd7 13. e5 $1 {Good move.} Ne8 {was played in the game, but it's very passive.} (13... dxe5 {The key point is that after} 14. dxe5 Ng4 15. Bh7+ Kh8 16. Be4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ge4,Ye5,Rg4] I can defend e5 and the knight is misplaced on g4.}) 14. Bh7+ Kh8 15. Be4 c6 16. Qe2 {Black's position is quite ugly.} Nc7 17. exd6 Qxd6 18. Rfe1 Rad8 19. Qe3 Ba6 20. Ne5 {And in the complications, my opponent missed an important trick I had.} Nxe5 21. dxe5 Qxe5 22. Qxb6 Rxd1 23. Rxd1 Bxc4 24. f4 $1 {And Black loses a piece.} Qxf4 25. Qc5 $18 {[%csl Rc4,Rf8] Game over. Basso-Kosic, 1-0, Paracin 2020.}) 9. cxd5 (9. e3 {is possible, but you need to take care about this structure now:} dxc4 10. Bxc4 O-O {[%csl Gb7] The bishop is good on b7, but it is also interesting:} 11. O-O-O $5 $13 {There are many good ways to play this position.}) 9... Nxd5 $1 {is the best move.} (9... exd5 10. e3 $14 {But here White is definitely slightly better, I will show you my game against GM Vorobiov.} O-O 11. Bd3 {Normal development moves followed:} Qe7 12. O-O Nbd7 {You can play this position in many ways, I opted for} 13. Nd2 {[%cal Rf6e4,Ga1e1,Gf2f4,Gd2f3,Gf3e5] To prevent Ne4 and also introduce new expansion plans.} c5 {[%csl Rd5] He played c5, so now I change my plan to target the d5 pawn.} 14. Rfe1 Rfc8 15. Bf5 {[%csl Rc8,Gf5] Good bishop move, against the rook.} g6 16. Bh3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gg2g3,Gh3g2] And the bishop is rerouted to a better diagonal.} Re8 17. Red1 cxd4 18. exd4 Bc6 {Symmetrical position, but slowly my opponent collapsed.} 19. g3 Qd6 20. Rac1 Rac8 21. Qb3 Rb8 $6 {allowed me to play} 22. Nb5 $1 {Removing the defender of d5 pawn.} Bxb5 23. Qxb5 Rbc8 24. Nf1 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf1e3,Gh3g2] I collected d5 pawn and then had no troubles to convert. Basso-Vorobiov, 1-0, Amantea 2018.}) 10. g3 {Probably g3 is the best, but after something like} (10. e4 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Nd7 $132 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gc7c5,Ga8c8] Black has some extra tempi, and the queen is not fantastic on c2.}) 10... Nd7 11. Bg2 O-O 12. O-O c5 13. Rfd1 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1] Of course, it is very playable, Catalan style. But it is difficult to talk about an advantage, more pleasant for sure though (+0,20 for the engine).}) (8. Qf4 {is a bit strange way to play, I don't love the queen on f4.} d5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 {has to be played.} (9... exd5 $2 {would be a mistake:} 10. Nb5 $1 {And concrete problems.} Na6 11. Qe5+ Qe7 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. e3 $16 {Positional domination.}) 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 $1 {Strong move.} 11. Qxc7 Nd7 $44 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ga8c8,Ge8g8,Gd5b5] Black has huge compensation.}) 8... O-O {The most logical move.} (8... d6 {If Black plays without d5, we are always happy.} 9. Bd3 Nbd7 10. e4 {[%cal Ge1c1] We spent a tempo, but we can play for long castle next.} e5 11. O-O-O O-O 12. Rhe1 $14 {[%cal Gc1b1,Gd3c2] White has a lot of useful moves, better for White.}) (8... d5 {I think it's more logical on the next move, because White has} 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bb5+ $5 {Extra option.}) 9. Bd3 d5 {And now d5.} 10. cxd5 exd5 (10... Nxd5 {is another story, because we are already well developed.} 11. Nxd5 Bxd5 (11... Qxd5 $6 12. Qc2 {[%csl Rc7,Rh7] Double attack.} h6 13. Qxc7 $16 {[%csl Gd3] White is fully developed, no compensation for Black.}) 12. Rc1 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gd3b1,Gd2d3] Pressure on the c-file and also against h7.} h6 (12... Nd7 $2 13. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Rc7,Rh7] Double attack.}) 13. Bb1 $40 {[%cal Gd2d3] Big attacking chances.}) 11. O-O {And here we can play in the same style as my game against Vorobiov, or even without Qc2.} Nbd7 12. b4 $5 $14 {This is not a Carlsbad, because Black's bishop is on b7.}) (6... d6 {is not a great move.} 7. Nc3 O-O (7... Nbd7 {The same story as in the main line, but even worse version for Black.} 8. e4 e5 9. O-O-O $1 {Strong move, and the position is just worse for Black.} Qe7 (9... exd4 {is just a bad positional move.} 10. Nxd4 O-O 11. f3 $16 {[%csl Ra5,Gb5,Rc7][%cal Gd4b5,Yc7c6,Gg2g4,Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Gg4g5] Especially, because of the a5 move, White is strategically much better.}) 10. Nb5 $5 {is also a possible concrete option.} (10. g4 $5 {is even possible.} Nxg4 $6 {is met with} 11. Rg1 $16) 10... Nxe4 (10... Qd8 $2 {is not posssible.} 11. dxe5 $18 {And problems with the d-file.}) 11. Qe1 $1 {And the evaluation is +1 after} Ndf6 12. Bd3 c6 13. Nxd6+ Nxd6 14. dxe5 $16 {Much better for White, thanks to the development.}) 8. e4 Nc6 {Main move.} 9. O-O-O $1 {is maybe even stronger, with the same idea of Rd1.} (9. Rd1 {That's why it's important to include this move, to stop e5.} Qe7 {Once Black plays Qe7, we can develop.} (9... e5 $2 {just loses material.} 10. dxe5 $16 {[%csl Rd8] Pawn up.}) 10. Be2 e5 {[%csl Re7] Here d5 is possible, but we also have ideas against the queen with} 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Nd5 $14 {That is a useful point to know.}) (9. Be2 $6 {If you just develop, the key concept is that Black can play} e5 10. d5 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Gc6e7] And after d5, the knight has a good square after} Ne7 $1 $11 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Ge7g6] And Black is doing great.}) 9... Qe7 10. Kb1 e5 11. dxe5 $14 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gb7b5] And it's all because of the a5 move, Black has no plan on the queenside.}) (6... d5 {will anyways transpose to castle.} 7. Nc3 O-O {See under 6...0-0.}) (6... a4 $6 {has been tried, but it is just premature, because White can attack it.} 7. Nc3 d6 8. Qc2 {Black needs to play} Bd7 {Ugly move to defend the pawn and after} 9. O-O-O $16 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gg2g4] Very easy play.}) 7. Nc3 d5 {White can play this position in many ways:} (7... d6 {is also a possible move under.} 8. e4 Nc6 9. O-O-O {Transposes to 6...d6.}) 8. Qc2 $5 {I like this move. Only 3 games here. Definitely playable.} (8. cxd5 {also possible.} Nxd5 {is not so good here.} (8... exd5 9. Qf4) 9. e4 Nxc3 10. bxc3 {[%csl Ra5] In the Semi-Tarrasch structure, the pawn is clearly misplaced.} c5 11. Bd3 $14) (8. e3 {was played in a recent game Warmerdam-Vidit, 2024.} Qe7 9. Rc1 b6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Be2 {was played in the game.} (11. Bd3 {I would have prefered the bishop on d3 at least.}) (11. Ne5 $5 {You can also play with the Ne5, because it is difficult for Black to develop.} Bb7 (11... Nbd7 {is met with} 12. Nc6 $16) 12. Bd3 Nbd7 13. f4 $14 {looks very interesting.}) 11... Bb7 (11... Nbd7 {was better to stop Ne5.}) 12. O-O {Again Ne5 was an option.} Rd8 13. Ne5 {He played it now.} Nbd7 14. f4 $1 $14 {Of course, and White is better.} (14. Nd3 $6 {was played, but it's too conservative.} Ne4 $11 {And Black was doing fine.})) 8... Nbd7 {Solid move.} (8... dxc4 {looks pleasant for White after} 9. e4 {Bxc4 is the idea, so Black should play something concrete:} c5 10. dxc5 Qc7 11. O-O-O $5 {You can play with long castle, if you want to be creative.} (11. Bxc4 {is also quite simple.} Qxc5 12. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Ra7a6,Rb7b5] The b5 square is weak, no a6-b5 plan, Black is worse.}) 11... Nbd7 (11... Qxc5 12. e5 $40 {[%cal Gc3e4,Gf3g5] With attacking ideas.}) 12. Bxc4 Qxc5 13. Qe2 $36 {You can try to play for e5.}) (8... c5 {is normal, but as usual, it weakens the b5 square.} 9. dxc5 Qe7 $6 (9... dxc4 10. e4 {transposes to 8...dxc4.}) 10. Na4 $16 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Ga4b6] And again the pawn being on a5 weakens Black's structure. Nb6 is a strong idea.}) 9. cxd5 {We can go for the Carlsbad structure now.} exd5 10. e3 c6 11. Bd3 {[%csl Ra5] The pawn on a5 is not great, for example:} Re8 12. O-O Nf8 13. h3 $14 {Typical position, but the pawn on a5 is not ideal. Na4-Nc5 is an idea, b4-b5. Definitely a good version for White.} *

