{[%evp 0,33,34,30,30,-3,-3,5,42,42,59,60,55,45,46,45,42,45,55,55,77,54,45,33,38,23,35,18,31,45,52,50,60,19,19,19]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 c5 {In the last chapter about 4.Bd2, we still have to check 4...c5, which is an ambitious line and a good one for Black.} 5. Bxb4 {White should take on b4, otherwise Black's last move is justified.} cxb4 {Here White tried many systems.} 6. a3 $5 {I suggest you to play this practical move. I have always played this line, with good results.} (6. g3 {[%csl Rc4] is the most common move, but I don't like it because very often Black will have counterplay against the c4 pawn. This is exactly what Black is aiming for, and it would make a great repertoire for Black!}) 6... bxa3 {Black's most critical move. How to recapture?} (6... Nc6 $2 {is just bad, because of} 7. d5 $1 $16) (6... Qe7 {is also bad, because White can play normal moves, and the queen is not always useful.} 7. e3 b6 8. Be2 Bb7 9. O-O O-O {And at some moment, White can} 10. axb4 $5 {And the queen will be misplaced on b4.} Qxb4 11. Nc3 {[%csl Rb4] And taking on b2 is not good for concrete reasons:} Qxb2 $2 12. Qd3 Qb4 13. c5 $1 $16 {[%cal Gf1b1] The queen is in big trouble.}) 7. Rxa3 {Of course, with the rook! The knight belongs to c3 and we don't want to ruin our structure.} O-O {Black will need to play castle anyway.} (7... b6 {has also been tried.} 8. Nc3 Bb7 9. d5 $5 {But we can play with d5, using the fact that Black's bishop is already on b7.} (9. e3 {is possible.} O-O 10. Bd3 {And some position like:} Nc6 11. e4 Nb4 12. Bb1 a5 13. e5 {Which is also playable.} Ne8 14. Ne4 $36) (9. Nb5 $6 {Maybe some players are scared of this move, but objectively Black has full compensation after} O-O 10. Nxa7 Nc6 11. Nb5 Nb4 $44 {Good compensation.}) 9... O-O (9... exd5 10. cxd5 O-O {Here we are not in time to play e4 for concrete reasons:} 11. e3 {But we can play with e3.} (11. e4 $6 {is met with} Re8 $1 12. Bd3 Nxd5 $1 $132 {Tactical point.}) 11... a5 12. Bc4 Na6 13. O-O {And we want to play e4 now.} Re8 (13... Nb4 {is met with} 14. e4 $1 $16 {Which is very strong.}) 14. Nb5 {A lot of ideas for White.} d6 15. Nfd4 $14 {Nice squares for the knights.}) 10. e4 d6 11. Be2 e5 {Typical position, but the bishop is committed to b7.} 12. O-O (12. c5 $5 {This positional idea is also interesting.} bxc5 13. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gc4a5] Not only compensation, but some advantage for White.}) 12... Nbd7 {can be met with} (12... a5 {is met with} 13. c5 $1 {similar to 12.c5.}) 13. Nb5 $1 $14 {Which is a bit annoying.}) 8. Nc3 {[%cal Gd7d5,Yd7d6,Yb7b6,Yc8b7] The main position. Black has 3 possible approaches: 1) with d5, 2) with d6-e5 and 3) with b6 (followed by a5-Nc6-Nb4-Bb7 etc.), but it depends on the position.} d6 (8... d5 {is not a bad move, but also not particularly critical, White will get a game here.} 9. e3 {I prefer to start with e3.} (9. cxd5 {is possible to start with this as well, but it allows some extra ideas for Black, for example:} exd5 10. e3 Bf5 $5 $146 {A possible novelty for the engine.} 11. Qb3 Nc6 $1 12. Qxb7 Bd7 $44 {And Black has some compensation.}) 9... dxc4 {is the only extra idea if we start with e3.} (9... b6 {will be met with} 10. cxd5 exd5 {Here you can play as you wish, but you may pay attention to} (10... Nxd5 {If Black takes with the knight,} 11. Nxd5 $146 {It's a novelty, but quite an obvious move.} Qxd5 12. Bd3 Bb7 13. O-O {And we can play this position, for example:} a5 14. e4 Qd8 15. Qe2 Nc6 16. Qe3 $14 {[%csl Ya3][%cal Gd3b1,Gh2h4,Ya3h3] And sometimes the rook on a3 can be quite useful, because it can join via the 3rd rank.}) 11. Bb5 $5 $146 {Quite a strange move, but what is the idea? For now to stop Nc6.} (11. Bd3 {was my choice against IM Lapshun, in Riga 2022.} Nc6 12. Ne5 Nxe5 $2 {My opponent took, but now I can seize the initiative with} (12... Nb4 $1 $146 {had to be played and after} 13. Bb1 a5 $1 $132 {[%cal Gc8a6] The bishop gets to a6, that's why I prefer 11.Bb5.}) 13. dxe5 Ng4 14. Ra4 $1 {was even stronger and a nice idea to keep in mind.} (14. h3 {I played this move, and it was a complicated game after} Qh4 $13) 14... Nxe5 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16. Qh5+ Kg8 17. Qxe5 $16 {White has a fantastic position.}) 11... Bb7 12. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb5a4,Ga4b3] Again Nc6 is not possible. And sometimes White has the idea to place the bishop on b3 and start pressuring the d5 pawn.}) (9... Nc6 {is also met with} 10. cxd5 {Since we want to develop the f1 bishop, it is a good moment to take.} exd5 (10... Nxd5 11. Bd3 {We already discussed this type of positions, and after} Nxc3 {You can take with} 12. bxc3 $14 {or the rook, in both cases White is slightly better.}) 11. Bb5 $5 {Once again I like this plan.} Nb4 {Logical, the best square for the knight.} 12. O-O $146 {There are no games, but we can follow some normal moves:} Bf5 13. Ne5 Qe7 14. Qf3 Bg6 {And sooner or later} 15. Ba4 $5 $14 {[%csl Gb3,Rd5][%cal Ga4b3] The bishop on b3 will stand well, putting pressure on d5.}) 10. Bxc4 {But it is not dangerous for White.} b6 {Very logical.} 11. O-O Bb7 {And in these positions, White always has a game, for example:} 12. Bd3 {To prepare e4 and control Ne4.} (12. Re1 $5 {With idea of e4.} Ne4 13. Bd3 Nxc3 14. bxc3 $14 {[%cal Ge3e4,Ge4e5,Yf3d2] The structure is very playable, White definitely has something.}) 12... a5 $1 {is the best move for Black, to introduce the Ba6 idea.} (12... Nbd7 13. Qe2 $14 {Good position.}) 13. Re1 Ba6 {Black plays their plan.} 14. e4 {We can grab the center.} (14. Bb1 {Black can start their counterplay with} b5 $1 $132) 14... Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Na6 {Logical continuation and now} 16. Raa1 $5 {The rook on a3 was not doing much, so we can spend a tempo to improve it.} Nb4 17. Qd2 $14 {Position is playable and slightly better for White.}) (8... b6 {is the third approach, but how to reach it? Because here} 9. e4 $1 {is strong.} d6 10. Bd3 $16 {White has a big center and a pleasant advantage.}) (8... Nc6 9. e3 d6 {Transposes to the 8...d6.}) 9. e3 Nc6 10. Be2 e5 {is the most common move, Black's second approach.} (10... b6 {was played against me by young IM Samant, now he is a GM.} 11. d5 $1 {Very important move.} Nb4 12. Nd4 {What I played is also good enough.} (12. dxe6 {also leads to a good advantage.} fxe6 13. Nd4 $14 {Pleasant advantage.}) 12... a5 (12... e5 $4 {doesn't work for concrete reasons.} 13. Nc6 $1 Nxc6 14. dxc6 $18 {[%cal Ge2f3,Gb2b4,Gc3d5,Gb4b5] And Black's position is just lost.}) 13. O-O exd5 $2 {My opponent took, but it is a huge mistake.} (13... Bd7 {had to be played, and accept that I will take on e6.} 14. dxe6 fxe6 15. Ndb5 $14 {White has all the fun here, but with the engine maybe Black can resist somehow.}) 14. cxd5 {[%csl Gd4] And Black's strucutre is very bad. It was an instructive win, I wanted to share it with you:} Bb7 15. e4 Nd7 16. Ncb5 {[%csl Gb5,Rd6][%cal Ga3h3] To attack the pawn and also the a3 rook can join the attack.} Nc5 17. Nf5 $1 Nxe4 18. Qd4 {Double attack.} Nf6 19. Rg3 g6 20. Nh6+ {I repeated the position once.} Kg7 21. Nf5+ Kg8 22. Nbxd6 {Now I took.} Bxd5 23. Qe5 {[%cal Gf5e7] To introduce Ne7+.} Nc6 24. Qc3 Nb4 25. Rd1 {And Black collapsed.} Ra7 26. Nc8 $1 $18 {Last touch, and my opponent resigned.}) (10... Nb4 {If Black starts with this move, followed by b6:} 11. O-O b6 {Black's third approach.} 12. e4 $146 {is my recommendation.} (12. d5 $2 {Don't play this move, because after} e5 $1 $13 {[%csl Rf3] We didn't manage to capture on e6, and our knight is not on d4.}) 12... Bb7 13. d5 $5 {is already a option now, and the most interesting one, because after} (13. e5 {The same plan as after 10...a5, but here maybe after} dxe5 14. Nxe5 Nd7 $13 {It is an improved version for Black, because the pawn is still on a7, but of course, playable for White.}) (13. Nd2 $5 {You can play this position.} a5 14. Qb1 $13 {Possible, but not exceptional.}) 13... e5 14. Nd2 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gf2f4] The bishop is worse on b7.} Bc8 {Black will sooner or later will need to lose a tempo with the bishop.} (14... a5 {With the bishop on c8, the position would be more or less fine, but here White can play} 15. f4 exf4 16. Rxf4 $14 {[%cal Gd2f3,Gf3d4] And the bishop is misplaced.}) 15. f4 exf4 16. Rxf4 Qe7 17. Nf3 $14 {It's an interesting way to play.}) (10... a5 11. O-O Nb4 {has to be played in order to play b6.} (11... b6 $2 {is a mistake, because of} 12. d5 $1 Nb4 13. Nd4 {transposing to my game against Aditya.}) 12. e4 $5 {We go for the e4-e5 plan.} (12. d5 $6 {is not good now.} e5 $1 $132 {[%csl Rf3]}) (12. Na2 {was played in some games, but Black is fine after} Nxa2 13. Rxa2 b6 $11) 12... b6 $146 {A novelty, but in general, the whole approach is very rare for Black.} (12... Nd7 {was played in Granda Zuniga-Nikolic.} 13. Nb5 $1 {Strong move.} Qe7 14. Qd2 b6 15. Re3 $1 $146 {I prefer this move and after} (15. Qg5 $14 {was played in the game, but it is not in the spirit.}) 15... Bb7 16. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4] White has the center, the coordination and the space. Of course, White is better.}) 13. e5 {My recommendation, and I like this plan.} (13. Ne1 {is also possible, but not super fantastic.} Bb7 14. f3 Rc8 15. Nc2 Nh5 $1 {Strong move.} 16. Rf2 $13 {Still playable.}) 13... dxe5 14. Nxe5 {[%cal Ge2f3] Probably this position is the best they can achieve in the 4...c5 line.} Bb7 {Logical move.} (14... Nd7 {is a concrete try.} 15. f4 {I suggest to support the knight.} (15. Bf3 {The point is that this move is met with} Nxe5 $1 16. Bxa8 Nxc4 $44 {And Black has compensation.}) 15... Bb7 16. Qd2 {We can play.} (16. Bf3 $6 {is not advisable now, because after} Bxf3 17. Rxf3 Nxe5 18. fxe5 {The structure is not the same, and the rook is out of the game:} Rc8 19. b3 f6 $36 {Black has some activity.}) 16... Qe7 (16... Nxe5 17. fxe5 {This is advantage for White, for example:} f6 18. exf6 Rxf6 19. Raa1 $14) 17. Nxd7 Qxd7 18. Rd1 $14 {[%cal Ge2f1,Gd2f2,Ga3a1] We can play for a long game here, +0.30 for the engine.}) 15. Bf3 Bxf3 16. Nxf3 {I think Black is more or less fine if they know the maneuver:} Ne8 $1 {[%cal Ge8d6] with idea of Nd6, but White can still play:} 17. Qe2 Nd6 18. Raa1 {To improve the rook.} Rc8 19. b3 $14 {Slightly more pleasant for White, but not too much.}) 11. O-O {[%csl Ya4][%cal Gd4e5,Gd1b3,Yf1d1,Yc3d5] And our idea that very often, White has the reaction of taking on e5, developing the queen to b3 or a4, and continue with Rd1-Nd5.} Bg4 {By far the main move.} (11... Bf5 {can be met with} 12. Qb3 $1 {Good move, tempo against b7.} exd4 {Black can take on d4, but it is not a problem for us.} 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. exd4 $14 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Ge2f3] Better structure and better pieces, and concrete problems with the queenside pawns for Black.}) (11... Re8 {can be met with the standard reaction:} 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Qb3 $14 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gc3d5] Good grip in the center.}) (11... Qe7 $2 {is probably a bad move, because of the immediate} 12. Nd5 $1 $16 {And Black has concrete problems.}) 12. h3 {Useful move.} Bh5 {Most common continuation. And here I always knew a safe way for a good advantage, but engine found something new for White:} (12... Bxf3 $5 {Maybe it is the best to take, but it is of course, very sad for Black after} 13. Bxf3 exd4 14. exd4 $14 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gd2f4,Gf1a1,Yb2b4,Yb4b5] White can increase the pressure.}) 13. dxe5 $5 {I still prefer my old idea.} (13. g4 $5 $146 {Novelty and engine claims that White's position is good after:} Bg6 14. Qb3 {And the line continues:} Rb8 15. d5 $1 {You need to know some lines, but they are quite forced.} e4 $1 16. dxc6 bxc6 17. Qd1 exf3 18. Bxf3 d5 19. cxd5 cxd5 20. Nxd5 Nxd5 21. Bxd5 Rxb2 22. Rxa7 $16 {Black has some drawing chances, but White is a pawn up.}) 13... dxe5 14. Qa4 $5 $146 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gc3d5] I had this move in my analysis back in 2017, and up to this day it is still a novelty.} Qe7 15. Rd1 Rfd8 {Normal move, and of course:} 16. Nd5 $1 {And the line gets quite forced after} Nxd5 17. cxd5 e4 $1 {Only good move.} 18. dxc6 exf3 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. gxf3 Qg5+ {Don't worry, it is just a check.} 21. Kf1 bxc6 22. Qxc6 $14 {Pawn up, good chances to play for a win.} *

