{[%evp 0,10,24,27,30,18,6,14,33,33,34,27,36]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Be7 {Regarding our repertoire from the "1.d4 According to Dreev" series, this is the only issue. However, it is not an objective problem but rather a matter of transpositions. That being said, it’s extremely unlikely that Black will play this line. Why? 1) If Black plays 3...Bb4+, he must be well-prepared against 4.Nd2 (First opening to know: Bogo-Indian with 4.Nd2). 2) He must also be ready to face the Nimzo-Indian in case White plays 3.Nc3 or even 3...Bb4+ 4.Nc3 (Second opening to know: Nimzo-Indian). 3) Now, we can play g3, and if Black follows up with d5, he must be prepared for 4...Bb4+ in the Catalan (Third opening to know: Catalan with 4...Bb4+). 4) Finally, we can also play 4.Nc3 d5, and now 5.Bf4 or 5.Bg5, leading to a QGD setup with 4...Be7 (Fourth opening to know: Queen’s Gambit Declined with 4...Be7). As you can see, playing 4...Be7 is highly impractical for Black, and our opponent won’t even realize that this move poses a challenge for our repertoire!} 5. Nc3 (5. g3 d5 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O {Transposes to the 4...Bb4+ 5.Bd2 Be7 Catalan, which is a respected line, but not part of our series "1.d4 According to Dreev".}) 5... d5 {[%cal Gd2f4,Yf4g5] now you can play 5.Bf4 or 5.Bg5, which are also respected lines, but not part of our series "1.d4 According to Dreev". In summary, even though this may theoretically seem like an issue for our repertoire, in practice, it is highly unlikely that an opponent will choose this path, making our preparation solid and reliable.} *

