{[%evp 0,12,30,16,21,14,14,14,26,27,27,22,22,11,52]} 1. d4 {Hi all! In this second section we will study 4.Nd2 variation. It's true, 4.Bd2 is much easier to play, but because of the 4.Bd2 Be7 move-order problem, we have decided to offer you also 4.Nd2, and it will be entirely presented by me. 4.Nd2 will be extremely useful also to increase your general positional understanding of all the 1.d4 structures.} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 O-O {Black's most common continuation.} (4... b6 {this is Black's second most important move.} 5. a3 Bxd2+ {In Chapter 9, I will logically explain how we should recapture on d2, depending on Black's 4th move, as this decision plays a crucial role in the position.}) (4... c5 {old passive move. We will analyze it in Chapter 14.}) (4... a5 {This is a tricky move, and you should first study Chapter 12 before diving into it. We will cover it in Chapter 14.}) (4... d5 5. Qa4+ ({you can also play} 5. g3 {transposing in Catalan part 2, but 5.Qa4+ is more interesting right now.}) 5... Nc6 6. a3 {Chapter 14.}) (4... d6 {rare but interesting. This is one of the rare cases where I don't want to play 5.a3.} 5. g3 {will be my recommendation in Chapter 11.} ({after} 5. a3 Bxd2+ {we don't have a suitable recapture. Why? More about this in Chapter 11 :)})) 5. a3 Be7 (5... Bxd2+ {it's always a question to understand how should we recapture. You will see my opinion in Chapter 10.}) 6. e4 d5 {This was Black's old mainline, but it is very risky, which is why, in the last 3-4 years, Bogo-Indian players have been searching for new alternatives. We will examine this in Chapter 12.} (6... d6 {more solid than 6...d5, but a bit passive. Very often, we will have KID structures where Black's Be7 is misplaced. More about it in Chapter 13.}) *

