{[%evp 0,49,25,26,18,-17,3,6,29,23,33,31,22,-13,3,13,7,-32,18,9,21,17,27,23,23,0,2,-1,-2,-8,-45,-55,-14,-3,0,0,33,38,20,66,66,66,48,75,77,57,88,80,89,89,89,94]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 {Black plays a hybrid version of Bogo/Queen's Indian.} 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Nxd2 $5 {my recommendation. We step aside from the big theory and try to play something more interesting!} (6. Bxd2 {not so interesting now, because after} Bb7 7. Bg5 {[%csl Ge8] Black's king is still on e8, which means he can potentially play h6 followed by g5 at some point. For example:} h6 {[%cal Gg7g5]} 8. Bh4 d6 9. e3 g5 10. Bg3 Ne4 $132) (6. Qxd2 {The big mainline. Of course, you can play it, but it requires extensive study, and in my opinion, there is a specific line that poses a serious challenge.} Bb7 7. e3 d5 $5 {There are only 17 recorded games, but many strong Grandmasters have played it recently.} (7... O-O {is Black's old mainline, which is also very playable for him.}) 8. Bd3 {or 8.Be2 would be the same.} (8. b3 {prophylactic move against dxc4, but Black can now play for c5:} O-O 9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. Be2 c5 11. O-O Rc8 {you can play it, but it's not easy to show something.} 12. Rac1 Ne4 13. Qd3 dxc4 14. bxc4 Qf6 $132) 8... dxc4 {Black's idea.} 9. Bxc4 Nbd7 10. O-O O-O $132 {[%cal Gc7c5] we have two bishops, but Black's pieces are well placed, and it's not easy to show smething.} 11. b4 {looks logical, but it's still nothing special:} a5 12. b5 c5 13. bxc6 Bxc6 $132 {Black is doing well.}) 6... Bb7 {only logical move, otherwise we will continue with e2-e4.} 7. e3 O-O (7... d6 8. Bd3 $5 {we can play in the same style as after 7...00.} (8. b3 $5 {[%csl Yd6] also possible because Black has already played d6.}) 8... Bxg2 (8... O-O 9. O-O {transposes in 7...00.}) 9. Rg1 Bb7 {[%csl Rg7] the only difference is that now g7 is hanging:} 10. Rxg7 Nbd7 11. Qe2 {Black is not doing terribly, but I like White's chances:} Qe7 12. Rg3 $5 {useful move.} ({Black might consider} 12. b4 a5 $132) 12... O-O-O 13. b4 $132 {[%cal Gc1b2,Ge1c1] Bb2-000 next. I think It's easier to play for White, but for the computer it's close to equal.}) 8. Bd3 $5 {[%csl Yg2] We are ready to sacrifice g2.} (8. b3 {You can certainly start with 8.b3, but I prefer beginning with 8.Bd3 because we might not always need to play b3 followed by Bb2 in the future.} d5 $5) 8... d5 {[%csl Gd2] Compared to the 6.Qxd2 variation, we are now better prepared against d5 because, in the event of dxc4, we will always have the option to recapture with the knight.} (8... Bxg2 {It is certainly a critical move, but it has only been played twice. In the resulting positions, we will always have more than sufficient compensation for the pawn. Moreover, it will be impossible to analyze all the variations in depth for both us and our opponent, as the position offers compensation but does not lead to forced play.} 9. Rg1 Bb7 10. b3 $5 $146 {This is my recommendation, and it's a novelty.} (10. e4 {ambitious try.} d6 {necessary to stop e4-e5.} 11. Nb3 $5 $146 {[%cal Gc1h6] The best, according to the engine, and we are preparing Bh6. Of course, there are many possible moves, but engine's first line continues like this:} Nbd7 12. Bh6 Ne8 13. Qh5 f5 (13... e5 $5 {also deserves attention.} 14. O-O-O Kh8 15. Bd2 $13) 14. exf5 exf5 15. Bxf5 Qe7+ 16. Kf1 Ndf6 17. Qh4 Kh8 18. Bg5 Qf7 19. d5 Ba6 20. Bd3 $13 {As you’ve seen, 10.e4 leads to very sharp and complex lines, and what I’ve shown you is just the tip of the iceberg! While 10.e4 is a valid alternative, to be honest, I prefer 10.b3.}) 10... d5 {the best, according to the engine. I can understand it because Black wants to immediately block White's Bb2.} (10... d6 11. Bb2 Nbd7 12. Qe2 $36 {[%cal Ge1c1] 000 next, and we have more than compensation.}) 11. Bb2 Nbd7 12. cxd5 $5 {I like this direction.} (12. Qe2 $5 {[%cal Ge1c1] deserves attention.}) (12. Qf3 {concrete approach.} dxc4 13. Bxh7+ Kxh7 14. Qxb7 cxb3 15. Qg2 g6 16. O-O-O {equal for the engine, but in real life the game can finish in a few moves.} c5 17. d5 $5 $13) 12... exd5 (12... Bxd5 $2 13. e4 $16) 13. Qf3 $44 {[%cal Ge1c1] very good compensation. It's not advantage, but it's an interesting position for sure.}) (8... c5 $6 {is Black's most common continuation, but it's not good:} 9. dxc5 bxc5 10. b3 $1 $146 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gc1b2] we will have a fantastic and unchallenged bishop on b2.} d6 11. Bb2 $14 {suitable position.} Nbd7 12. O-O a5 {Van Foreest-Naiditsch, 2024. Van Foreest played Qc2, but maybe a better plan could be:} 13. Qe2 $5 Qe7 14. f4 $36 {I am sure that every player will like White's chances.}) (8... d6 {Black continues with the standard d6-Nbd7 development, but it's a suitable scenario for us:} 9. O-O Nbd7 10. b4 $14 {[%cal Gc1b2] Black might be solid, but it's clear that he is at least slightly worse. For the engine, the evaluation is +0,70.}) 9. O-O c5 {probably the best.} (9... dxc4 $6 {this approach was interesting when White's knight was on f3, but not here:} 10. Nxc4 $1 {[%csl Gc4]} Qd5 (10... Nbd7 11. b4 $16 {serious positional advantage.}) 11. f3 Rd8 12. Be2 $14 {[%cal Rc7c5,Gd4c5] when Black plays c5, we can take dxc5. This position was reached in the game Carlsen-Gazik, 2024. Once again, we see that the 6.Nxd2 variation has recently been chosen even by the world's top players.}) (9... Nbd7 {standard move, but Black faces some problems after} 10. b4 $1 (10. b3 e5 $1 {is strong.} 11. cxd5 Bxd5 12. e4 Bb7 13. d5 c6 14. d6 Nc5 $1 $13 {[%csl Yb3,Gc5] that's why 10.b4 is better than 10.b3!}) 10... e5 {it's not the same as after 10.b3:} (10... c5 11. dxc5 Ne5 $1 (11... bxc5 $2 12. Bb2 $16 {serious positional advantage.}) 12. Be2 bxc5 13. Bb2 Nxc4 14. Nxc4 dxc4 15. Bxc4 cxb4 16. axb4 $14 {Winning this position is not trivial—you need good technique—but it is risk-free and certainly enjoyable for everyone.}) (10... a5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 (11... exd5 12. b5 $16 {big positional advantage.}) 12. b5 $14) 11. cxd5 Bxd5 12. e4 Bb7 13. d5 c6 14. d6 $1 $16 {[%cal Rd7c5,Gc1b2,Gf2f4,Gd2c4] Black doesn't have the key Nc5 resource. We will just continue with Bb2-f4 (eventually Nc4).}) (9... a5 {Black prevents b4, but not always b5 will be good and we can just play with b3:} 10. b3 Nbd7 11. Bb2 $14 {We have a Colle style position, but with 2 differences: - Black misses the important dark squared bishop; - a5 move slightly weakens Black's position (usually the pawn stays on a6 in the Colle). We can safely say that for sure White is better.}) 10. dxc5 {[%csl Gc5] necessary move, but it's also in our plans.} (10. b3 $6 {be careful!} dxc4 11. Nxc4 Qd5 $1 12. f3 Rd8 $13 {looks very unclear, but maybe Black already has some initiative.}) 10... bxc5 {While Black's position is objectively fine, we have many interesting directions, and our position is for sure playable and enjoyable.} 11. b3 {objectively, this is White's most interesting continuation, but it's still not a novelty.} (11. b4 $5 {Interesting line. If you like it, you can play it and save some time by avoiding the need to study the following variations.} Nc6 12. bxc5 Ne5 13. Be2 dxc4 14. Nxc4 Nxc4 15. Bxc4 $14 {you need very high-class tecnique to have chances here with the two bishops.}) (11. Re1 $5 $146 {my idea.} Nc6 12. Bf1 $14 {[%csl Gf1] Bf1 stays very well (for example, after cxd5-Qxd5, it will not be attacked and g2 will be already defended).} (12. cxd5 Qxd5 $1 $11)) 11... d4 $1 $146 {only Black's good move not to end-up in a long-term worse position.} (11... e5 $2 {active move for Black, but it's a mistake!} 12. Bb2 e4 (12... d4 13. exd4 exd4 14. b4 $16) 13. Bc2 d4 14. exd4 cxd4 {[%csl Yd4,Ye4] d4 and e4 are strong or weak?} 15. b4 $16 {[%csl Rd4,Re4] For the engine the answer is clear: d4 and e4 are weak, and White already has a big advantage.}) (11... Nc6 $6 {most natural move, but now it's bad!} 12. Bb2 d4 13. exd4 Nxd4 (13... cxd4 14. b4 $16) 14. b4 e5 15. Re1 Re8 16. Nb3 $16) (11... Nbd7 {also natural, but after} 12. Bb2 $16 {Black is just positionally worse.}) 12. Re1 $5 {could be an interesting direction.} (12. Nf3 {engine's top choice.} dxe3 $1 13. Bxe3 Qc7 $1 {Black has to find many best moves because the position itself is not good for him, only with concrete moves he can equalize:} 14. h3 {[%cal Rf6g4] against Ng4.} Rd8 15. Qe2 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Nc6 17. Rfd1 Rab8 $11 {This is "0.00", accoriding to the engine.}) 12... dxe3 $1 {looks anti-positional, but it's the best.} (12... e5 13. Bb2 {we are not afraid of e4.} e4 $2 14. Nxe4 $1 {strong positional sacrifice.} Bxe4 (14... Nxe4 15. exd4 $18) 15. Bxe4 Nxe4 16. exd4 Nf6 17. dxc5 $16 {It's not only compensation, but also a big advantage. 3 pawns + strong Bb2 are better than Black's 2 knights.}) 13. Rxe3 {[%cal Gc1b2] if we play Bb2 we are just better.} Qd4 {[%cal Rc1b2] only move, with the idea to stop Bb2.} 14. Ra2 Ng4 $1 {again, only move for Black.} 15. Ne4 {The position is ready to explode!} f5 $1 {only move again!} (15... Nxe3 $2 16. Bxe3 $18 {[%cal Ge4c5] Nxc5 next, and according to the engine, it's already +3,00.}) 16. Qe2 $1 {and now, finally Black has a choice, but not an easy one.} fxe4 $2 {most natural continuation, but it's bad because of the following forced continuation:} (16... Rf7 $1 {computer move, but who will play it? :)} 17. Bb1 Nc6 $1 (17... Nxe3 $6 18. Bxe3 Qe5 19. f4 Qc7 20. Nxc5 $14) 18. h3 Nxe3 19. Bxe3 Qd8 20. Nxc5 $44 {[%eval 0,0] for the engine, but still very interesting and Black had to find a countless number of best moves.}) 17. Bxe4 {I will not comment because all the rest will be only moves for both sides:} Nxe3 18. Bxb7 Ng4 $1 19. Rd2 $1 Qa1 $1 20. Rd1 Nxf2 21. Re1 Qf6 22. Bxa8 Nd3 23. Bg5 $1 Qxg5 24. Qxd3 Qf4 25. Qe2 $16 {We can finally stop and say that White has a good positional advantage. I think that we have found a very nice DreevDreams exercise right now!} *

