{[%evp 0,31,29,13,19,6,6,18,39,17,27,22,22,31,29,6,6,-2,-2,-1,22,-5,2,32,42,38,52,47,42,42,50,73,68,18]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 O-O 5. a3 Bxd2+ {This variation may seem similar to the one we previously examined, 4...b6, but there are some important differences that are worth noting.} 6. Bxd2 {[%csl Rg8] My recommendation: Compared to the 4...b6 line, it's important to note that Black has already castled. Why? Because once we play Bg5, Black will no longer have the h6-g5 ideas available.} (6. Qxd2 d5 7. e3 b6 {we spoke about this position in the 4...b6 Chapter.}) (6. Nxd2 {was our move against 4...b6, but here it is less interesting:} d6 7. e3 (7. e4 $2 {mistake now because of} Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4] and we cannot comfortably defend d4.} 8. d5 {looks logical, but...} exd5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 {strong idea.} 10. exd5 Re8+ 11. Be2 Nd4 $17 {Black is seriously better.}) 7... e5 $132 {no problem for Black.}) 6... b6 {Black's most common continuation.} (6... Ne4 $6 {too early for this approach because we can just play} 7. Bf4 {[%csl Re4,Gf4] and Black's knight on e4 could easily be misplaced.} b6 (7... d6 {allows} 8. Qc2 {and Black must play f5, which is already an achievement for us.} f5 (8... Nf6 $2 9. e4 $16) 9. e3 b6 (9... Nd7 {[%cal Gd7f6] Black is ready to protect Ne4.} 10. Bd3 Ndf6 11. O-O b6 {most logical continuation.} 12. Ng5 $5 Nxg5 13. Bxg5 Bb7 14. f3 $16 {[%cal Ga1e1,Ge3e4] Rae1 next, and at some moment e4.}) 10. g4 $1 {not the only way, but the most interesting one.} Bb7 11. gxf5 exf5 12. Rg1 $16 {[%cal Gd4d5,Gf3d4] d5-Nd4 next.}) 8. g3 Bb7 9. Bg2 {[%csl Re4] Black's best move is Nf6 back, and this already shows everything.} Nf6 {you can play as you wish:} (9... d6 $2 10. Ng5 $1 $16) 10. d5 $5 (10. O-O Be4 11. Bh3 $14 {[%cal Gf1e1,Gf3d2] Re1-Nd2 next, typical slightly better position.}) 10... exd5 11. Nh4 {very good version of the Queen's Indian gambit.} c6 12. Nf5 dxc4 13. Nd6 Bc8 $1 (13... Ba6 $2 {[%csl Rb8] bad because it's impossible now to develop Nb8.} 14. Bg5 $1 h6 15. h4 $1 $18 {White is already winning.}) 14. Rc1 (14. Bg5 Na6 $1 $13) 14... Na6 15. Rxc4 Nc7 16. O-O $14 {We dominate the board and it's for sure more than full compensation.}) (6... d5 {any move is fine now, for example} 7. Qc2 (7. Rc1 $5 $14 {also interesting.}) 7... b6 8. e3 Bb7 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Rc1 $14 {Nowadays, nobody plays in this fashion with Black.}) (6... d6 {[%cal Ge6e5] Black thinks that the priority is e6-e5.} 7. Bg5 (7. Qc2 {will soon transpose into the Nimzo 4.Qc2.}) 7... Nbd7 (7... h6 {if Black immediately includes h6-Bh4, we have some extra ideas:} 8. Bh4 Qe7 (8... Nbd7 9. g4 $36) 9. g4 $36 {That's why it's probably better for Black not to play immediately h6.}) (7... Qe7 {[%csl Gc8] Black begins with Qe7 instead of Nbd7 because he hopes to eventually develop the bishop on g4 or f5.} 8. e3 e5 9. Be2 h6 10. Bh4 Bf5 {was recently played in the game Theodorou-Praggnanandhaa, World Blitz 2024.} 11. h3 $5 $146 {[%cal Gh4g3,Gg3h2] we make sure that our bishop will have the h2 square.} (11. O-O {was White's continuation, but after} g5 $1 12. Bg3 Ne4 $11 {Black is doing great.}) 11... Nbd7 {Black's normal moves are Nbd7+Re8+a5.} 12. O-O Rfe8 13. Rc1 {[%cal Gf1e1] useful move.} a5 14. Re1 $14 {[%cal Gf3d2,Ge2f1] Nd2, then maybe Bf1 next. We can play many prophylactic moves and have a long game where we are slightly better.}) 8. e3 e5 (8... b6 9. Bd3 Bb7 10. Nd2 {transposes in 6...b6.}) 9. Be2 h6 10. Bh4 Qe7 {this is an instructive moment.} 11. h3 $5 $146 {[%csl Yh2,Gh4][%cal Yh4g3,Yg3h2] My recommendation: we make sure that Bh4 will have the h2 square.} ({if we immediately play 00, then Black can continue with} 11. O-O g5 12. Bg3 Ne4 $132 {[%cal Ge4g3,Gf7f5] Nxg3, followed by f7-f5 and the position could become very unclear.}) 11... exd4 {probably the best.} (11... b6 12. O-O Bb7 13. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Ge2d3] Bd3 next, with a typical advantage.}) 12. Nxd4 Nc5 13. O-O a5 14. b3 $14 {Of course, it's slightly better for White, even if Black is solid.}) 7. Bg5 Bb7 8. e3 d6 9. Bd3 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Rh7h6,Yg5h4,Rg7g5] It's important to note that Black cannot play h6-g5 with the king on g8. However, this option will become available as soon as White castles.} Nbd7 10. Nd2 $5 {I have played this move in 2015, and I invented it OTB. Now, it's my recommendation. Now Black faces a very difficult task: deciding how to proceed and whether to include h6-Bh4 or not. As we will see, if Black intends to capture on g2, it is better to include h6-g5 first. On the other hand, if Black plans to continue with c7-c5, then it’s better not to include h6-g5! As you can imagine, these are all subtle details that are extremely difficult for our opponent to fully grasp over the board.} (10. O-O {would be White's most normal continuation, but Black can now continue with} h6 11. Bh4 g5 $1 12. Bg3 Ne4 $132 {[%cal Gf7f5,Ye4g3] f5 next, and Black has a very good counterplay. Very important that Black can play Nxg3 whenever he wants.}) (10. Bh4 $5 {you can also play some generic prophylactic move like} e5 (10... c5 11. O-O $14) 11. Bc2 $14 {[%csl Gc2,Gh4] Bh4+Bc2 are two very good prophylactic moves.}) 10... c5 {Black's most solid continuation.} (10... Bxg2 $6 {if Black wants to take on g2, then it's better for him to include h6-g5 first.} 11. Rg1 Bb7 12. Ne4 $1 {this move works very well here, but less well when h6-Bh4 is included.} Kh8 13. Nxf6 Nxf6 14. d5 $1 exd5 15. cxd5 Re8 $1 {only move.} (15... Bxd5 $2 16. Bc2 $1 {in this position, with h6-Bh4 included, Black would have the decisive g7-g5 resource.} Bb7 17. Qd4 $18) 16. Qa4 $1 {[%cal Ga4h4] we prepare Qh4.} Bxd5 17. Qh4 Be4 {[%csl Ge4] key defense for Black.} 18. Bxe4 Rxe4 19. Qxe4 Nxe4 20. Bxd8 Rxd8 21. b4 $16 {[%cal Ga1c1,Ge1e2] I don't know if this endgame is winning, but for sure we have very good chances.}) (10... h6 11. Bh4 Bxg2 {It's not a move for everyone, but only for the most brave ones! But it's for sure critical and important to check.} (11... e5 12. O-O $14 {The position itself is at least slightly worse for Black.}) (11... c5 {[%csl Gh4] this plan is not good now when h6-Bh4 is included:} 12. O-O cxd4 (12... Qc7 13. Rc1 $14 {dream position: two bishops and no forced lines.}) 13. exd4 d5 14. Re1 dxc4 15. Nxc4 $16 {[%csl Gh4,Rh6] h6-Bh4 is clearly favorable for White compared to the mainline 10...c5, where, as we will see, White plays Bh4 even without waiting for Black's h6.}) 12. Rg1 Bb7 13. Qe2 {my recommendation.} (13. Ne4 {was stronger when h6-Bh4 was not included:} Kh8 14. Nxf6 {it's important to check this move to compare 10...Bxg2 with 11...Bxg2:} (14. Qe2 $36 {is still interesting.}) 14... Nxf6 15. d5 $2 exd5 16. cxd5 Bxd5 17. Bc2 g5 $1 {[%csl Gg5] big difference between the two lines. Now, White is lost.}) 13... Qe8 {[%csl Ge8,Gf6][%cal Rh4d8] Necessary move to unpin Nf6.} 14. O-O-O Kh8 $1 {Black's best, according to the engine.} (14... e5 $6 {Happened in my game in 2015, and now White would have been better with:} 15. Bf5 $16 ({or} 15. d5 $16)) 15. f4 $36 {[%cal Gf4f5,Gg1g3,Gd1g1] Rg3-Rdg1 next, or f5 sometimes. For sure compensation, but I think even more. The engine evaluates with +0,40.}) 11. O-O cxd4 $1 $146 {Black's best continuation, in my opinion.} (11... Qc7 {was tried in some games, but White is just slightly better here:} 12. Rc1 Rac8 13. Re1 $14 {[%cal Gd3f1,Gg5h4] Bf1-Bh4 next. No need to study concrete lines here.}) 12. exd4 d5 {and now, we should be ready to play an IQP position.} 13. Re1 (13. b3 $6 {doesn't work well because of} e5 $1 $13) 13... dxc4 14. Nxc4 Qc7 15. Bh4 {[%cal Gh4g3] we prepare Bg3.} Qc6 16. Bf1 $14 {Engine shows +0,35, and I am sure that White is slightly better, but Black is solid, and this might be the most reliable position for him in this Chapter.} *

