{[%evp 0,27,19,17,27,6,6,6,30,25,32,34,22,30,40,42,39,31,34,42,48,13,16,44,2,17,14,14,11,14]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 d6 {Not very popular, but this is one of the rare cases (along with 4...d5 in Chapter 14) where my recommendation is not 5.a3.} 5. g3 {This is my recommendation against 4...d6.} ({First, let's discuss why we won’t play 5.a3. To understand this, we need to apply the knowledge from Chapters 9 and 10.} 5. a3 Bxd2+ {Now, we don't have a suitable recapture.} 6. Qxd2 {If you like Qxd2 positions, you can go for it. The advantage for White is that Black has already played d6, meaning he no longer has the immediate d5 option available (see the 4...b6 chapter). However, Qxd2 is still Qxd2—it leads to extensive theoretical lines, which I prefer to avoid.} (6. Nxd2 {We saw in the previous chapter that Nxd2 is not very interesting when Black has not played b6.} e5 $11) (6. Bxd2 b6 $5 {[%csl Gd2] As you already know, I don't like to play Bxd2 when Black's king is still on e8. We have already discussed the reason in the previous two chapters.} (6... O-O 7. Bg5 {transposes in Chapter 10.}))) 5... O-O {Mainline.} (5... Nbd7 6. Bg2 e5 7. O-O {Black has nothing better than} O-O {and we will analyze this position from the 5...00 move order.}) (5... c5 $6 {this is not very good now.} 6. Bg2 Nc6 7. a3 $1 Ba5 (7... Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 $16 {just better for White thanks to the two bishops.}) 8. dxc5 dxc5 9. O-O {[%csl Rc8] Bc8 is bad, for example:} O-O 10. Nb3 Bb6 11. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Gf4,Gg2] Our bishops are much stronger.}) (5... a5 6. Bg2 {Black must choose between 6...Nc6 and 6...00, and it will then transpose to 5...Nc6 or 5...00 move order.}) (5... Nc6 {Black's second mainline after 5...00.} 6. Bg2 a5 $1 {[%csl Ga5] Black's best. a5 defends Bb4 and prepares e6-e5.} (6... O-O 7. O-O {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gd2b3,Ga2a3] of course, this position can also be achieved from the 5...00 6.Bg2 Nc6 7.00 move order. Our threat is now Nb3 (or Nb1) after which Black's Bb4 will be in trouble.} Bxd2 {now I like} (7... a5 {[%csl Gg1] too late now, because White has already played 00 and it means that Nd2 is not pinned!} 8. Nb1 $1 a4 9. a3 {[%csl Ra4]} Ba5 10. Qxa4 $18) (7... e5 8. d5 Ne7 9. Nb3 $16 {[%csl Rb4] problems with Bb4.}) 8. Bxd2 $5 e5 9. d5 Ne7 10. Nh4 $1 $16 {[%cal Rf6e4,Ge2e4] not allowing Ne4 and with the idea to take on g6 in the case of Ng6. Our next move will probably be e2-e4.}) (6... e5 $6 7. d5 $1 {and Black must take on d2.} Bxd2+ (7... Ne7 $4 8. Qa4+ $18) 8. Nxd2 Ne7 9. O-O O-O 10. e4 $16 {positionally better for White.}) 7. a3 {the most critical move.} (7. O-O {natural, but Black can play} e5 $1 8. d5 Ne7 $132 {[%csl Ge7] Ne7 is good, and it's important that Bb4 is defended against Qa4+ ideas.}) 7... Bxd2+ 8. Bxd2 e5 {The key idea in these positions is to play d5 only after Black has already moved the queen to e7. Why? Because this prevents Black from positioning the knight on e7, which is a very good square for the knight.} 9. Bc3 $5 (9. d5 Ne7 $13 {[%csl Ge7] Ne7 is good.}) 9... Ne4 $1 {but this is a critical move.} (9... Qe7 $6 10. O-O O-O 11. d5 $14 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Rc6e7] Now we are ready for d5, because Black no longer has Ne7.}) 10. Nxe5 {we don't have anything better than to enter in the following concrete sequence:} Nxc3 11. Nxc6 Nxd1 12. Nxd8 Nxb2 13. Nxb7 Ra7 $1 {only move.} 14. O-O Nxc4 (14... Bxb7 $4 15. Rfb1 $1 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 {[%csl Re8,Rh8][%cal Gb1b8] very important that we have Rb8+ idea.} Rb7 17. Ra2 $18) (14... O-O {also possible, but we are slightly better also here:} 15. Rfb1 Nxc4 16. Rc1 Be6 17. Nc5 $5 dxc5 18. d5 $14) 15. Rfc1 Bxb7 16. Rxc4 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Rb7 (17... Kd7 18. Rb1 $14) 18. Rc6 Kd7 19. Ra6 Rb2 20. e3 Rc8 21. Rxa5 $14 {For the engine it's a draw, but in a practical game we have for sure chances.}) 6. Bg2 e5 $1 {This is a fantastic move and probably the best option for Black. Psychologically, it’s not easy for Black to play this move, as he must be prepared to play without a pawn. However, according to the computer, White has no way to achieve an objective advantage. That said, we have some interesting tries, and you can choose according to your style.} (6... Nc6 {we have already analyzed it via the 5...Nc6 move order.}) (6... Nbd7 $6 {[%csl Rd7] Black's knight on d7 is misplaced.} 7. O-O e5 8. Nb3 $1 {[%csl Rb4] very important move and Black has problems with Bb4.} exd4 9. Nfxd4 $16 {[%cal Ga2a3] a3 next and we will at least play with the two bishops.}) (6... Qe7 {Black's most common continuation, but I don't think that it's the best.} 7. O-O e5 (7... Bxd2 {Bxd2 is always possible, but almost never Black equalizes with it in the 4...d6 line:} 8. Qxd2 e5 9. dxe5 $5 {practical choice.} dxe5 10. b4 $14) 8. Nb3 {[%csl Rb4] Problems with Bb4.} exd4 9. Nfxd4 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4]} 10. Bf4 $5 {useful move and now we are more ready for a3, but of course Black can play} (10. a3 {is probably premature:} Bc5 11. Nxc5 dxc5 12. Nb5 Rd8 $132 {[%cal Gb8c6] Nc6 next.}) 10... a4 11. Nc2 $1 $146 {strong improvement.} (11. a3 {was played by Chigaev, but now Black has the strong} Bc3 $1 12. bxc3 axb3 13. Qxb3 Nbd7 $44 {[%csl Ra3,Rc3,Rc4][%cal Gd7c5] our pawns are very bad.}) 11... axb3 (11... d5 $5 {engine move, but it also doesn't fully equalize:} 12. Nbd4 dxc4 13. Nxb4 Qxb4 14. Bxc7 $14) 12. Nxb4 bxa2 13. Nxa2 $14 {[%cal Ga2c3] Nc3 next, and we are for sure slightly better.}) (6... a5 {also good move, but here we can get a playable position:} 7. O-O a4 8. Ne1 $5 {[%cal Ge1d3] Not the only move, but I like this idea.} e5 $146 {critical move, but Black should be prepared to play it.} (8... d5 9. Nd3 Be7 10. Qc2 $14 {fresh playable position.}) (8... c5 $146 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Nb1 $1 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3] Nc3 next.}) 9. Nc2 Na6 $1 (9... Ba5 $6 {logical but bad:} 10. b4 $1 axb3 11. axb3 Ra6 12. Bb2 $16) 10. Nxb4 Nxb4 11. d5 {[%cal Ga2a3] e are ready to play a3, and Black's best is} Bf5 $1 {after which, we can play for the advantage only after the fantastic} 12. Nb1 $3 c6 {the best, according to the engine.} (12... Nc2 $6 {critical but dubious because of} 13. e4 $1 Nxe4 14. g4 $1 Nxa1 (14... Bg6 15. Qxc2 Ng3 16. Qd1 Nxf1 17. Qxf1 $16 {not game over, but Black is worse for sure.}) 15. gxf5 Qh4 16. Na3 $14 {still complicated, but objectively White has an advantage.}) 13. Nc3 cxd5 14. cxd5 b5 $1 {important move, otherwise Black could be slightly worse.} 15. Bg5 $5 (15. Nxb5 Qb8 $1 16. Nc3 Nc2 17. Rb1 Na3 18. Ra1 Nc2 $11 {ends in an immediate draw by repetition.}) 15... h6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Nxb5 Rfb8 18. Nc3 a3 $1 19. bxa3 Rxa3 20. Qc1 Raa8 $1 $44 {According to the engine, Black has almost full compensation, but OTB I think it's still playable.}) 7. O-O $5 {Maybe it makes sense to play 7.00 without accepting the sacrificed pawn.} (7. dxe5 {of course, this is critical move and we should start from this one.} dxe5 8. Nxe5 {Black doesn't have any concrete way to restore material equality, but he can play normal positional moves and use the misplaced position of our Nd2.} Re8 9. Nef3 a5 {[%csl Ga5] a5 is necessary, otherwise we will continue with a3-b4 with an advantage.} ({or} 9... Nc6 10. O-O a5 {leads to the same.}) 10. O-O Nc6 11. a3 Bc5 {strangely enough, we don't have any clear way to be objectively better.} 12. Nb3 {the best, according to the engine.} (12. b3 {with Bb2 next looks logical, but after} Qe7 13. e3 Bf5 14. Bb2 Rad8 $44 {Black has a very good compensation.}) 12... Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Ne4 $1 {I can show you some small tries, but objectively it's equal:} 14. Nxc5 {the most critical move.} (14. Be3 $5 Bxe3 15. fxe3 {[%cal Gf3d4] we are ready for Nfd4, and if Black doesn't want to end-up slightly worse he should play the precise} Nf6 $1 {after which our best chance is} 16. Nfd4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Rxe3 18. c5 $11 {[%cal Gb2b4] maybe b4 next. It's still not a 100% draw, but objectively it's very close to equality, of course.}) 14... Nxc5 {[%csl Rb3,Re2] We have two problems: e2 is hanging and Black has the Nb3 idea.} 15. e4 $5 {This is the best, according to the engine.} Nb3 $1 (15... Nxe4 $2 16. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Rc7]}) 16. Rb1 Rxe4 17. Nd2 Nxd2 18. Bxd2 Rxc4 {we can try to play for the two bishops, for example:} 19. Bd5 Rc2 20. Be4 Rc4 21. f3 $11 {for sure, we have full compensation and maybe some very small practical pressure, but of course, it's very close to a draw.}) 7... Bxd2 (7... e4 {looks logical, but we have an interesting resource:} 8. a3 $1 Bxd2 (8... exf3 9. Nxf3 {[%csl Rb4] suddenly, Black's bishop is trapped.} Ba5 10. b4 Bb6 11. c5 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Gg2] slightly better for White thanks to the two bishops.}) 9. Nxd2 d5 10. Nb1 $5 $132 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gc1g5] Nc3-Bg5 next. We are not better if Black plays like an engine, but it's a fresh playable position.}) (7... exd4 8. Nxd4 $14 {Saric-Kurajica, 2008. Typical slightly better structure.}) 8. Bxd2 $5 $146 (8. Qxd2 {has been tried twice.} e4 9. Ne1 d5 $13 {worse version for White compared to 8.Bxd2.}) 8... e4 $1 9. Nh4 $5 {We try to get an interesting and complicated game.} (9. Ne1 d5 $132 {is Black's idea, maybe you can find something here, but I think that 9.Nh4 is more interesting from the practical perspective.}) 9... d5 $1 {This is Black's idea, the same as after 9.Ne1.} ({in the case of a normal move like} 9... Re8 {we can play} 10. d5 $1 $14 {[%cal Gd2c3] Bc3 next, and we have chances for an initiative.}) 10. f3 {and now I think it will not be easy for our opponent to understand OTB which is the best reaction.} dxc4 {first option, maybe the best.} (10... exf3 {second possibility.} 11. Rxf3 Be6 {necessary move, with Nbd7 next.} 12. Bg5 Nbd7 13. Nf5 $36 {[%cal Gf5g7] engine shows that sometimes we have Nxg7 ideas. Against an engine, you will never win, but OTB I can easily see Black losing this in the few next moves.}) 11. Bg5 {and now, Black must find an only move:} e3 $1 {I don't think it will be easy for everyone to find it.} 12. f4 $5 {The position is objectively equal, but still very rich, for example:} (12. Bxe3 Re8 {[%csl Rh4] We have problems with Nh4, for example:} 13. Bf2 g5 $1 14. g4 gxh4 15. Bxh4 $44 {White still has full compensation, but maximum for equality.}) 12... Nbd7 {looks logical, and now we can play in Catalan style.} 13. b3 cxb3 14. Qxb3 $44 {We have full compensation and the position is very interesting. In conclusion, against the super move 6...e5, you can choose to play 7.dxe5, which is safe but drawish, or 7.00, which leads to sharper and more complicated positions.} *

