1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 O-O 5. a3 Be7 6. e4 d5 {For many years, this was considered the mainline, but nowadays, Bogo-Indian players are looking for more practical options for Black.} 7. e5 {the only critical way.} (7. Qc2 {is not interesting because after} dxe4 8. Nxe4 Nxe4 9. Qxe4 c5 $11 {Black solves all the problems.}) (7. Bd3 {also not interesting:} dxe4 8. Nxe4 Nxe4 9. Bxe4 c5 $11 {Just equal.}) 7... Nfd7 (7... Ne4 $2 {is of course bad because of} 8. Bd3 Nxd2 9. Bxd2 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gh2h4] we have great attacking chances on the kingside.} dxc4 10. Bxc4 b6 {there are some old games here, but White has a huge advantage after} 11. Bd3 $1 Bb7 12. h4 $40 {[%cal Gf3g5,Gh1h3] Ng5 or Rh3 next. Black's position is much worse, maybe even lost already.}) 8. Bd3 $1 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gc7c5] It is crucial to understand the essence of this position. First, let’s make it clear that Black has strong counterplay in the center as soon as he plays c5. However, our chances lie entirely in the fact that we have excellent attacking prospects on the kingside. This fundamental idea will help us understand the upcoming moves for both sides.} (8. b4 {looks like a logical move because we stop c5, but Black is fine after} a5 $1 9. b5 c5 $1 $132) 8... c5 {As already mentioned, this is Black's idea.} 9. h4 $1 {We continue in the spirit of the position.} ({there is no time for standard moves like} 9. O-O {because after} Nc6 10. Re1 a5 $132 {[%csl Gc5,Gd5] Black has excellent counterplay in the center.}) {Now, Bxh7+ is already a deadly threat, for this reason Black has to immediately defend against it. The old move is 9...g6, but the best move is 9...h6.} 9... h6 $1 {the best.} (9... Nc6 $4 {let me just show you that this loses immediately:} 10. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 11. Ng5+ $18 {game over.}) (9... g6 {In the past, this was Black's most common continuation just because it looks more solid. But here White will get a good advantage:} 10. O-O {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gc1h6] Now we castle. The key point is that, thanks to the inclusion of h4 and g6, Black's dark squares have become weak, giving us ideas such as Bh6.} (10. h5 {looks tempting, but after} cxd4 11. Qc2 g5 $1 $132 {[%csl Gg8,Rh5] Black's king is safe thanks to our pawn on h5.}) 10... Nc6 (10... Bxh4 $2 {bad, but better to check it.} 11. Nxh4 Qxh4 12. Nf3 Qe7 13. Bg5 $18 {[%csl Rf6,Rg7,Rh6] dark squares are too weak for Black.}) ({or} 10... cxd4 11. Re1 Nc6 12. Nb3 {leads to the same position analyzed via the 10...Nc6 move order.}) 11. Nb3 cxd4 (11... Bxh4 12. Bh6 Re8 13. Re1 cxd4 {will be analyzed via the 11...cxd4 move order.}) (11... dxc4 $2 {is a bad move order for Black:} 12. Bxc4 cxd4 13. Re1 Bxh4 14. Bh6 Re8 15. Qc1 $1 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Gc1f4] We are ready for Qf4. We play Qc1 and not Qd2 just because now our bishop on c4 is protected, for example:} Nb6 16. Nxh4 Qxh4 (16... Nxc4 17. Bg5 $18) 17. Bg5 $18) 12. Re1 Bxh4 13. Bh6 Re8 {This position can arise from many move orders. Now, we have a lot of interesting options.} 14. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2f4] Engine's first choice. The idea is Qf4.} (14. Qc2 $5 $146 {also interesting.}) (14. Rc1 $5 {also deserves attention, for example:} Be7 {Gajewsky-Elsness, 2014.} 15. cxd5 $1 $146 exd5 16. e6 fxe6 17. Bb5 $36 {looks very interesting.}) 14... Be7 15. Qf4 {Black's position looks very bad, let's see what happens after Black's best moves:} Bf8 16. Rad1 f6 {only move.} (16... b6 $2 {Black tries to develop, but it's just a huge mistake.} 17. cxd5 exd5 18. Bb5 Bb7 19. Bxc6 Bxc6 20. Nbxd4 Bb7 21. Re3 $18 {[%csl Rb7] +4,00 evaluation.}) 17. exf6 Nxf6 18. Bg5 Nh5 $1 {Engine's idea.} (18... Bg7 $2 19. Nbxd4 $1 $16) 19. Qc1 Be7 20. Bxe7 Rxe7 21. Bf1 Bd7 22. Nbxd4 $16 {We can conclude that even if Black plays like an engine, his position is still very bad. For these reasons, 9...g6 is nowadays considered a mistake.}) 10. Bb1 {[%cal Gd1c2] We prepare Qc2. Of course, many years ago, this was considered too risky for Black, but modern engines have discovered incredible defensive resources.} cxd4 $1 {Black should play concrete moves if he wants to survive.} (10... Nc6 $2 {Black allows us to develop a killing attack:} 11. Qc2 f5 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. g4 $1 $18 {just game over.}) (10... Re8 $2 {[%cal Gd7f8]} 11. Ng5 $1 $18 {[%cal Gg5f7,Gd1h5,Gh1h3] too many threats.} (11. Qc2 Nf8 {is Black's idea.})) 11. cxd5 (11. Qc2 {looks very interesting, but unfrotunately after} f5 12. exf6 (12. cxd5 d3 $5 {extra option, that's why I start with 11.cxd5.} 13. Qxd3 Nc5 $13) 12... Nxf6 $132 {Black is doing fine.}) 11... exd5 12. Qc2 f5 13. Nb3 $1 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gb3d4,Gc1f4] Now that we have provoked the weakening move f7-f5, we completely change our game plan, shifting our focus to reclaiming the d4 square and consolidating the crucial e5 pawn. Normally, I would consider White to have excellent chances of achieving a clear positional advantage, but once again, the engine finds incredible defensive resources—fortunately, they are still not widely known! 🙂} (13. exf6 $6 Nxf6 $11 {once again, Black is fine here.}) 13... Nc6 14. Bf4 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yf4e5] Of course, we must protect our e5 pawn.} d3 $1 {this is the only problematic move for us.} (14... a5 {has been tried, but after} 15. Nbxd4 Nc5 16. Ba2 $5 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 $16 {White has consolidated and has a good positional advantage.}) (14... Nb6 {Black's idea is Nc4.} 15. Ba2 $1 {[%csl Ga2] our bishop is very useful on the a2-g8 diagonal.} (15. Nbxd4 $6 Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Nc4 $1 $132 {[%cal Gd8b6] Qb6 next and Black gets some counterplay.}) 15... Nc4 16. Rd1 $1 {We will take on d4 only when it's more suitable for us.} (16. Nbxd4 $6 {don't rush in recapturing the pawn.} Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Qb6 $132) 16... Qb6 17. O-O $16) (14... g5 $4 {is, of course, very bad:} 15. hxg5 hxg5 16. Nbxd4 gxf4 17. Nxf5 $18) (14... Qb6 $6 {most common move in human games, but it's bad:} 15. Ba2 Re8 {[%cal Gd7f8] Black plans Nf8-Ne6.} (15... Nc5 16. Nxc5 Qxc5 17. Qxc5 Bxc5 18. Bxd5+ $16 {big positional advantage.}) 16. O-O Nf8 17. Rad1 Ne6 {Rodshtein-Andreev, 2013. Nc1-Nd3 next, with a good positional advantage.} 18. Bd2 $1 $16 {[%csl Rd5,Rf5][%cal Gb3c1,Gc1d3]}) 15. Qxd3 a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4,Yd7c5] Black prepares a4, followed by Nc5.} (15... Nc5 $2 16. Nxc5 Bxc5 17. Ba2 $16 {Lupulescu-Smith, 2013.}) {Now, we have a lot of interesting options, but Black can hold if he plays like an engine.} 16. Qxd5+ {this is White's most natural continuation.} (16. Ba2 {looks interesting, but Black solves all the problems after} a4 $1 $146 17. Nbd4 Nc5 18. Qe2 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 Ne6 $11) (16. O-O $5 $146 {This could be an interesting option to get a complicated game.} a4 17. e6 $1 {this is my idea.} (17. Nbd4 Nc5 $11 {is fine for Black.}) 17... Nf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4] Black's knight goes to e4 via f6.} (17... Nc5 $2 18. Nxc5 Bxc5 19. Re1 $16 {positional advantage.}) 18. Nbd4 Ne4 $1 {without Ne4, Black is worse.} 19. Ba2 {looks very nice for White, but again the engine finds strong defensive resources.} Bc5 $1 (19... Kh7 $6 20. Nb5 $1 $16) 20. Rac1 Kh7 $1 {another strong move that Black should find.} (20... Re8 21. Be3 $14) 21. Nb5 {and now Black has two ways for an acceptable position:} Bxe6 $5 (21... Ne7 {White can play many interesting moves, but there is no advantage.} 22. Nc7 (22. Bc7 $5 {deserves attention.}) 22... Ra5 23. Rcd1 $13 {+0,20 for the engine, but of course very complicated.} (23. h5 $5 {deserves attention.})) 22. Nc7 Qe7 23. Nxa8 Rxa8 24. Bxd5 $5 {my recommendation.} Rd8 25. Bxe4 Rxd3 26. Bxd3 $13 {For the engine, this is equal, but OTB White could have interesting chances. For sure it will be a fight.}) 16... Kh8 {Black plays for compensation.} 17. Qd2 $1 (17. O-O $2 {mistake because of} Ndxe5 $1 $17) 17... Qb6 18. Nbd4 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 Rd8 $1 {[%csl Rd4] we have problems with Nd4, but we can play} 20. Nxf5 Nxe5 21. Qe2 Bxf5 22. Bxf5 {The position looks very nice for us: 2 bishops and one extra pawn, but with only moves Black can hold!} Ng6 $1 23. Be3 Qf6 24. Bg4 {the most solid option.} (24. Bc2 {has been tried in an email game, but Black is fine after} Qc6 $1 25. O-O Nxh4 $13) 24... Ne5 $1 {[%cal Ge5d3,Re1g1,Yf6h4] much stronger than Nxh4. Black threats Nd3+, and if we castle then Qxh4 is strong.} (24... Nxh4 25. O-O $14 {here we might have some small chances thanks to the 2 bishops.}) 25. Bg5 $1 {critical move.} Qd6 26. Rd1 Qc5 27. Be3 Rxd1+ 28. Qxd1 Qc6 29. O-O Rd8 30. Qe2 Nxg4 31. Qxg4 Qd7 $44 {We have an extra pawn, but according to the engine, Black has full compensation.} *

