{[%evp 0,37,26,29,21,6,6,6,38,26,25,14,15,19,23,9,10,18,7,22,32,23,38,-20,-14,-9,-14,-34,-31,-30,36,36,36,44,52,52,52,71,71,54]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 O-O 5. a3 Be7 6. e4 d6 {[%csl Ye7] A solid system. It somewhat resembles the King's Indian, except that Black's bishop is on e7 instead of g7.} 7. Bd3 {my recommendation.} (7. Qc2 Nfd7 {[%csl Yc2] I am not sure that Qc2 is so useful.}) (7. Be2 {White's most common continuation, but I declined it because of} e5 $1 {it's not Black's most common continuation, but it's a problem, in my opinion.} 8. dxe5 {critical.} ({if we don't accept the pawn, after the logical moves} 8. O-O exd4 9. Nxd4 Nfd7 $1 $11 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Ge7f6] Black is ready for Bf6, and his position is absolutely fine. Our Nd2 is bad.}) 8... dxe5 9. Nxe5 Re8 10. O-O Bf8 11. f4 {only chance to maintain the extra pawn, but after} (11. Nef3 Nxe4 $11 {just equal.}) 11... a5 $1 $13 {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6c5] Na6-Nc5 is coming, and Black's position is very interesting, in my opinion.}) 7... e5 $1 {Black can play this move immediately, and he should do it.} (7... c5 {is positionally bad because of} 8. d5 $16 {[%csl Re7] We have a good Benoni because Be7 is misplaced in this structure.}) (7... a5 {rare, but possible. Because of the fact that Black has played a useful but not concrete move, my recommendation is} 8. Nb1 $5 {[%cal Gb1c3] with the idea to improve our knight.} e5 9. d5 Na6 10. Nc3 Nc5 11. Bc2 $16 {good version of the King's Indian.}) (7... Nfd7 {Black prepares e5, and now we have more than one good option:} 8. Nf1 $5 {[%cal Yf1e3,Yf1g3] I like this deep idea. We want to improve the knight on e3 or g3.} (8. b3 {useful move (no a5-a4 idea for Black).} e5 9. d5 $14) 8... e5 9. d5 $1 $146 (9. Ng3 $6 exd4 $1 10. Nxd4 Bf6 $13 {Andreikin-Postny.}) 9... a5 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gf7f5] Black plans Nc5-f5.} 10. b3 {[%cal Ra5a4] useful to stop a4 ideas.} Nc5 11. Bc2 f5 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Bxf5 Rxf5 14. Ng3 $14 {must be slightly better for White.}) (7... Nbd7 {[%cal Ge6e5] Black prepares e5, but as we will see in the mainline, e6-e5 was also possible immediately, so why should Black start with Nbd7?} 8. O-O e5 ({if Black doesn't play e5, we are just better in many ways.} 8... b6 $6 9. e5 $5 (9. Re1 $16) 9... dxe5 10. dxe5 Ng4 11. Qc2 {very risky for Black, for example:} h6 (11... Ngxe5 12. Bxh7+ Kh8 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Be4 Rb8 15. Qc3 $16 {[%csl Rh8][%cal Gc3h3]}) 12. Bh7+ Kh8 13. Be4 Rb8 14. Qc3 {[%cal Gh2h3] h3 is our idea, so Black must play} f6 {and now, we have a very strong move:} 15. Bc2 $1 {[%cal Gc3d3] preparing Qd3. Both captures on e5 are bad:} Ngxe5 (15... Ndxe5 16. h3 $18) (15... fxe5 {maybe is the best, but it already shows that Black's position is bad.} 16. h3 Ngf6 17. Nh4 $16) 16. Nd4 $1 $18 {[%csl Re6,Rh8][%cal Gd4e6,Yf2f4,Yc3d3] Nxe6 next, or f4 followed by Qd3.}) {We can play many moves. I like the useful} 9. h3 $5 Re8 10. Nb1 $146 {[%cal Gb1c3] we have time to improve our knight.} exd4 11. Nxd4 Bf8 12. Nc3 Nc5 13. Re1 Nxd3 14. Qxd3 $14 {typical positional advantage.}) 8. O-O exd4 $1 {the most critical.} (8... Nfd7 {too passive:} 9. d5 {[%csl Re7] As we have seen in the sidelines at move 7, we are usually happy to transpose in the KID structure, because Black's Be7 is often misplaced.} ({not} 9. Re1 $6 exd4 10. Nxd4 Nc6 $132 {and Black is doing great.}) 9... Nc5 10. Bc2 a5 11. b3 {[%cal Ra5a4] useful move against a4.} f5 (11... c6 {now we have time for our standard positional idea} 12. Nb1 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3]}) 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Bxf5 Rxf5 14. Rb1 {We have a classical structure and a classical pressure. For example:} Rf8 15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 Nd3 17. Ne4 Nxc1 18. Rxc1 Nd7 19. Qd3 Qe8 20. Ra1 Qg6 21. Rfe1 $14 {What is the plan in these positions? Consolidate, slowly improve, and wait for opponent's mistake!}) 9. Nxd4 Re8 {Black's most common move, and probably the strongest.} (9... Nfd7 {We have more than one interesting option:} 10. f4 (10. Nf5 $5 $146 {[%cal Gf5e3]} Bf6 11. Ne3 $14 {[%cal Ge3d5,Ya3a4,Ya1a3] is for sure at least more pleasant for us. We can continue later with Nd5, and maybe a4-Ra3 to activate our rook.}) 10... Bf6 11. N2f3 Nc6 12. Bc2 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 {must be slightly better for White, for example:} b6 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc8b7,Gb7e4] probably the best because Bb7 will put pressure against e4.} (13... Re8 14. Be3 Nc5 15. Qf3 $14 {[%cal Ga1e1] standard positional advantage.}) 14. Nc6 $5 {[%cal Gc6b4,Gb4d5] we rotate the knight to d5!} Qe8 15. Nb4 Bb7 16. Nd5 $14 {According to the engine, it's only +0,30, but from a human eye it looks more!}) (9... Nc6 $6 {this move has been played by many strong players, and now White has a nice way to get an advantage:} 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Nb3 $1 {[%csl Ya5,Gd4][%cal Gb3d4,Yb3a5] Our knight will go to a5 (or to d4 sometimes).} c5 12. Na5 Bd7 13. f4 $14 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Gc1d2,Gd2c3,Gd1f3] Bd2-Bc3-Qf3 next, with a very pleasant advantage.}) 10. b4 {[%cal Gc1b2] It's my recommendation. We take space on the queenside and prepare Bb2.} (10. Nb1 {unfortunately, we don't have time for it:} Nc6 $1 $11) (10. f4 {looks active, but Black can play the strong} d5 $1 $146 11. cxd5 Bc5 {and he has full compensation:} 12. N2b3 Bb6 {[%csl Re4]} 13. Qc2 a5 $1 $13 {[%cal Ga5a4]}) (10. Bc2 $5 {deserves attention.}) 10... a5 {probably the best because it immediately forces us to take a decision on the queenside.} (10... Bf8 11. Bb2 $14 {typical slightly better position.}) (10... c5 11. Nc2 $14 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gc2e3] Bb2-Ne3 next.}) (10... Nfd7 11. Nf5 $5 {I like this idea.} Bf6 12. Rb1 $14 {[%cal Gf5e3] our knight could go to the nice e3 square.}) 11. b5 $146 {We have to play b5. I know that it looks strange to give up on the c5 square, but it's more important not to allow Black's Ra8 to activate.} (11. Bb2 {has been tried in some games, but after} axb4 12. axb4 Rxa1 13. Qxa1 Nfd7 $132 {[%cal Ge7f6,Yb8c6] Bf6, then Nc6, and Black is fine.}) 11... Nfd7 {[%csl Gd7,Ge7][%cal Ge7f6,Gd7c5] better than Nbd7 because Black will also have Bf6 ideas.} (11... Nbd7 12. Bb2 Bf8 13. Bc2 Nc5 14. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4] f4 next.}) 12. Bb2 Bf6 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gc7c5] Now, Black prepares a concrete idea: c5! which uses the undefended position of our Bb2.} 13. Qb1 $5 {My offer is to just defend our bishop, so that c5 is no longer an idea for Black.} (13. Re1 {allows} c5 $1 14. bxc6 Nxc6 $11) 13... Nc5 (13... c5 $2 {just a positional mistake now.} 14. Ne2 $16 {[%csl Rd6]}) 14. Bc2 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Gb1a2,Ga1e1] our only problem is Ra1, but it looks like we will have time to play Qa2 and Rae1 because Black cannot improve his position too much.} Ne6 $1 {Black's most accurate continuation, and now we have two good options:} (14... Nbd7 {looks logical, but} 15. f4 {[%cal Gb1a2,Ga1e1]} a4 16. Qa2 $14 {[%cal Ga1e1] Rae1 next, and once we solve the problem of our Ra1, we are better.}) 15. Nxe6 {tactical option.} (15. N2f3 $5 $14 {positional option.}) 15... Bxe6 16. e5 $5 Bxe5 17. Bxh7+ Kf8 {[%csl Yf8] safer than Kh8.} (17... Kh8 $6 18. Be4 $36 {[%csl Rh8] Kh8 is more in danger than Kf8.}) 18. Be4 Bxb2 19. Qxb2 $36 {Looks interesting. We can conclude that 7...d6 is a solid variation, and Black essentially has two main approaches: 1) Allowing White to push d4-d5, which would leave Black with an inferior version of the King’s Indian Defense due to the awkward placement of the bishop on e7. 2) Playing exd4, which I believe is the more interesting option for Black. However, it requires a high level of precision to be played correctly, and in most cases, it leads to unexplored positions.} *

