1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 d5 (4... c5 {It is a concrete move and was once quite popular. It is not bad in an absolute sense, but Black ends up in passive positions with no real chances to play for a win. This is probably why the 4...c5 variation has been largely abandoned in recent years.} 5. a3 $1 {this is the only interesting way for White.} (5. dxc5 Bxc5 {Black will have a good hedgehog.}) 5... Bxd2+ 6. Bxd2 {my recommendation. It's more interesting than 6.Qxd2.} (6. Qxd2 {doesn't offer much, in my opinion.} cxd4 7. Nxd4 d5 8. cxd5 Qxd5 {White has several tries, but Black is fine everywhere, for example:} 9. f3 e5 10. Nc2 Qb3 $11 {Grischuk-Kramnik, 2024.}) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 d5 {we need to have some ideas here.} 8. cxd5 {only interesting way.} (8. e3 {not interesting, in my opinion.} O-O 9. Qc2 e5 10. Nf3 Nc6 $132) 8... Qxd5 (8... Nxd5 $2 {bad because of} 9. e4 Nf6 10. Nb5 $1 Nxe4 11. Be3 $16 {too many threats and too much activity.}) 9. e3 {and now, Black should be very careful.} Bd7 $1 {the best.} (9... a6 $2 {just loses a tempo:} 10. Bb4 e5 $2 {Mohr-Hoelzl, 1988.} (10... Bd7 11. Rc1 Nc6 12. Rc5 Qe4 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Qc1 $16 {[%csl Re8]}) 11. Rc1 $1 Nc6 12. Rc5 $18) (9... O-O $6 {looks like it's Black's priority, but no!} 10. Bb4 Rd8 {allows} (10... Re8 11. Nb5 $1 Na6 12. Qxd5 Nxd5 13. Ba5 $14 {Two bishops and more activity.}) 11. Be7 Rd7 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Qg4+ Kf8 {Lorbron-Kortschnoj, 1986.} 14. Bb5 $5 $36 {this is clearly not equal.}) 10. Rc1 {[%cal Gd2b4,Gc1c5] Rc1 is a nice move because sometimes we will have Bb4-Rc5 ideas.} O-O (10... Nc6 {Black prevents Bb4, but now} 11. Nb5 $1 {is strong.} Rc8 {Van Wely - Rozentalis, 2010.} 12. Bc3 $1 Qxd1+ 13. Rxd1 Ke7 14. Nd6 Rc7 15. e4 $1 $16) 11. Bb4 (11. Qb3 $5 {engine's recommendation, but after} Nc6 12. Qxd5 Nxd5 $14 {I am not sure that this is the best version for our pair of bishops.}) 11... Rc8 {probably the best.} (11... Rd8 $2 {allows} 12. Be7 Re8 13. Rc5 Qe4 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Rg1 $16 {[%cal Gf1d3] Bd3 next.}) (11... Re8 {allows} 12. Rc5 Qe4 13. Nf3 $36 {[%cal Gf1d3] Bd3 is our idea. The position looks very risky:} Bc6 {probably the best.} 14. Bd3 Qg4 15. Rg1 $5 {[%cal Gc5g5] preparing Rg5.} Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Qxf3 17. gxf3 Nd5 18. Bd2 $14) 12. Rxc8+ Bxc8 13. Be2 Na6 {only way to finish the development.} (13... Qxg2 $2 14. Bf3 Qg6 15. Nf5 $1 $18) (13... e5 14. Nf3 Nc6 15. Bc3 $14 {we can just play for the two bishops.}) (13... Nc6 $2 14. Bf3 $1 $16) 14. Bf3 {and now Black needs to find another strong move.} Qd7 $1 {[%csl Gd7] it's important for Black to have a defended queen on d7.} (14... Qd8 15. Bc3 $14 Nd5 16. Ne2 $16 {[%csl Rd8] Qd8 is not defended, that's why 14...Qd7 is better.}) 15. Bc3 Nd5 {Now, I recommend to allow Black to exchange our bishop:} 16. Qd2 (16. Bd2 e5 $13 {looks unclear.}) 16... Nxc3 17. Qxc3 {[%csl Ra6] our plan is to play against the bad knight on a6.} Qc7 18. Kd2 $14 {The king is ready for the endgame. Rc1 next, and it's clear that White's pieces are much more active. Like always, against an engine, you will not win, but against a human there are very good chances.}) (4... a5 $5 {tricky move. We should apply the knowledge from Chapter 12 to successfully handle variation.} 5. a3 Be7 {the logical continuation.} (5... Bxd2+ {doesn't make sense now, because after} 6. Bxd2 $14 {[%csl Ra5] Compared to Chapters 9 and 10, the move a5 is not so useful for Black.}) 6. e4 d5 {the most critical move.} (6... d6 {[%csl Ra5] doesn't make too much sense now because a5 is useful, but not Black's priority compared to Chapter 13.} 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O e5 9. Bc2 $14) 7. Qc2 $1 {[%csl Gc2] If 7.e5 allows Black to achieve an improved version of the position compared to Chapter 12, the move 7.Qc2 has the opposite effect: here, Black's move a5 will be much less useful than if he had castled.} (7. e5 {would be the logical continuation if we follow the spirit of Chapter 12, but here there is a huge difference!} Nfd7 8. Bd3 c5 $132 {[%csl Ge8][%cal Rh2h4] Black has excellent counterplay in the center. In the variation from Chapter 12, Black had castled instead of playing a5, and in that case, our idea was to play h4! for a quick kingside attack. However, here Black's king is still on e8, which means any kingside attack won't be as strong. This is precisely the most important idea behind the 4...a5 variation.}) 7... c5 $1 {The standard 7...dxe4 doesn't equalize, that's why it's necessary for Black to play something different, and 7...c5 is the best option.} (7... dxe4 {standard continuation.} 8. Nxe4 Nxe4 (8... Nbd7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Bf4 $16) 9. Qxe4 c5 {[%csl Ra5] now a5 is not so useful, and after} 10. Be3 $14 {[%cal Ge1c1] our idea is to continue with 000, and we have a good advantage.}) 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bb5+ {the most interesting move.} Bd7 (9... Nc6 $146 {also possible, but nobody ever tried it. I think that we can just play} 10. dxc5 O-O 11. O-O $14 {And there's no need to study anything further here, as we have an extra pawn, a promising engine evaluation, and this position has never occurred in practical play.}) 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {this is the critical position of the 4...a5 variation. Only one game was played: Ivanchuk-Fedorchuk, 2017.} 11. O-O (11. e5 $5 $146 {interesting deviation.} Nh5 12. Nb3 {we force c4. In this way, Black will no longer put pressure against our center.} c4 13. Nc5 Bxc5 14. dxc5 {[%csl Rh5] looks interesting because Nh5 is misplaced. At some moment we could play h3-g4, but the engine thinks that it's equal because of} Na6 15. Be3 Rc8 16. Rd1 Nxc5 17. h3 $5 $44 {[%cal Gg2g4] interesting but a bit risky of course.} Nd3+ (17... g6 18. Bh6 $36) 18. Rxd3 cxd3 19. Qxd3 $13 {White is not worse, but of course it's a position for three results.}) (11. dxc5 {not interesting now because of} Qb5 $1 $11 {[%cal Re1g1]}) 11... O-O {Ivanchuk played 12.e5, but I think it's more interesting} (11... dxe4 $146 {important possibility. It's a bit passive, but White should be prepared in order to pose problems.} 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 cxd4 (13... O-O $2 14. Re1 Bf6 15. dxc5 $16) 14. Nxd4 O-O {[%csl Ra5,Gd4] a5 is now a weakness and we have a good knight on d4, but the position could quickly be simplified.} 15. Nf5 {only chance.} Bf6 16. Qg4 {[%cal Gc1h6] we prepare Bh6.} g6 17. Nh6+ Kh8 $1 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Gf6g7] g7 square should be left for the bishop.} (17... Kg7 $2 {is natural, but bad because of} 18. Qf3 $1 {[%cal Gh6g4] Ng4 is our idea.} Qc6 {only move.} 19. Qg3 $40 {[%cal Gh6g4]}) 18. Qf3 Bg7 19. Rd1 {not easy for Black to understand how to continue.} Qe6 $1 {only move.} (19... Qe7 $6 {natural but bad:} 20. Bg5 $1 f6 (20... Qxg5 21. Nxf7+ $18) 21. Bf4 $16) 20. Qxb7 Nc6 {[%cal Ga8b8] Rab8 is the idea, but I offer to play} 21. Bf4 $14 {and enjoy your extra pawn. Against an engine, you will not win, but against a human, there are some chances.}) 12. dxc5 $5 $146 {simpler and more challenging.} ({This is how Ivanchuk game continued:} 12. e5 Nh5 13. Rd1 Rc8 (13... c4 $1 $36) 14. Nf1 cxd4 15. Qe2 Nc6 16. Nxd4 g6 17. e6 fxe6 18. Qxe6+ Qxe6 19. Nxe6 $14 {White got a slightly more pleasant endgame in Ivanchuk-Fedorchuk, 2017.}) 12... Nc6 {engine's top move, but it's not easy to play it:} (12... Rc8 13. e5 Ne8 14. Rd1 Bxc5 15. Qd3 $14 {[%cal Gd2b3,Yf3g5] Nb3 next (or Ng5 if Black doesn't play h6).}) (12... Qc6 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Yc6c5,Gf6d7] Black attacks c5 and also frees the d7 square for the knight.} 13. e5 (13. exd5 $5 {also interesting.} Qxd5 (13... Nxd5 $6 14. Ne4 $16) 14. Nc4 Bxc5 15. Be3 Bxe3 16. Nxe3 $14 {[%csl Ra5] a5 could be a weakness in this endgame.}) 13... Nfd7 14. Rd1 Nxc5 15. Nd4 Qa4 16. Qxa4 Nxa4 17. N2f3 $14 {more pleasant for White.}) 13. e5 Ng4 14. Re1 {[%csl Rg4] very dangerous to play with the knight on g4, and now the best is} f6 $1 15. e6 Qc8 $1 {but it's not easy to find f6+Qc8! In addition, the position was new from many moves, and we still have a nice-looking position and a +0,20 engine advantage. Here, you can try 16.Nb3 or 16.Rb1 and just play.} 16. Rb1 $5 (16. Nb3 $5 $14) 16... a4 17. b4 axb3 18. Nxb3 $14 {Nge5 only move, and you can continue forever, or just stop here.} (18. Rxb3 Ra5 $1 $11)) 5. Qa4+ {The most principled continuation.} ({Of course, you can play} 5. g3 {and directly transpose to our "Catalan part 2".}) 5... Nc6 6. a3 Be7 (6... Bd6 {not good because of} 7. c5 {coming with tempo.} Be7 8. b4 $16 {just seriously better for White.}) (6... Bxd2+ {Not absolutely bad, but it's a passive continuation.} 7. Bxd2 Ne4 ({it's very difficult for Black to play without Ne4.} 7... O-O 8. e3 {also here, only Ne4 is normal for Black, otherwise we just play with the two bishops.} Ne4 {transposes to 7...Ne4.}) (7... Bd7 8. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Gc2,Rd7] anyway we will play Qc2, so I think Bd7-Qc2 is a good inclusion for White.}) 8. e3 (8. Rd1 {I have tried Rd1 against Safarli, but I think 8.e3 is better.}) 8... O-O (8... Nxd2 9. Nxd2 O-O 10. Nf3 $14 {Just slightly better without any need to study theory.}) 9. Qc2 $1 {[%csl Rc6] Queen was misplaced on a4. We played Qa4 only to force Nc6, which is now misplaced.} (9. Bd3 {Unfortunately, it's not good because of} e5 $1 10. cxd5 Qxd5 $11) 9... Nxd2 (9... e5 $2 {not good now because of} 10. cxd5 $1 Nxd2 (10... Qxd5 $4 11. Bc4 $18) 11. dxc6 Nxf3+ 12. gxf3 exd4 13. O-O-O $16 {Shirov-Ebeling, 2019.}) 10. Qxd2 {standard playable position.} b6 (10... Qf6 11. Qc3 $1 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Re6e5] we prevent e5.} Re8 12. Rd1 $14) 11. cxd5 (11. Qc2 $5 Ba6 12. Bd3 h6 13. O-O Na5 14. cxd5 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 exd5 16. Rac1 $14 {not too much but playable.}) 11... exd5 12. Bd3 {with Black's pawn on b7 is absolutely equal, but with the pawn on b6 it's slightly better.} Ne7 13. b4 Bf5 14. O-O $14 {We can conclude that 6...Bxd2+ is not absolutely bad, but definitely passive for Black.}) 7. e3 O-O (7... Bd7 8. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Gc2,Rd7] Qc2-Bd7 is a good inclusion for White.}) (7... a5 $5 {Interesting line, which hides a nasty trap.} 8. b4 dxc4 (8... O-O {there are some old games here, but Black is worse:} 9. c5 Nb8 10. b5 c6 11. b6 Nbd7 12. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Gb6] Probably, with weaker engines, it was not clear how to evaluate this position, but now it's clear that White is better.}) 9. b5 $1 {important move, but after it, White secures some advantage.} (9. Nxc4 $2 {This is falling in Black's nasty trap!} b5 $1 10. Qxb5 Bd7 $17 {Black was already better in So-Mamedyarov, 2022.}) 9... Na7 (9... Nb8 10. Nxc4 O-O 11. Bd3 $14) (9... c3 10. Nb1 Na7 11. Nxc3 $14) 10. Nxc4 Bd7 11. Nce5 $14 {Gorshtein-Paichadze, 2024.}) 8. Qc2 {[%csl Gc2] We have already discussed the fact that Qa4 was misplaced and that we have played it at move 5 only to force Black's knight to go on c6, where it's now misplaced.} a5 {It's important for Black to stop b4.} (8... Re8 9. b4 $16 {[%csl Rc6] just better for White.}) (8... Nb8 $5 {possible to play it also now, but after} 9. b3 Nbd7 (9... c5 $2 {Prohaszka-Kosic, 2006.} 10. dxc5 $1 Bxc5 11. cxd5 Qxd5 12. Bb2 $16) 10. Bb2 {Black's best by far is a5, which directly transposes to the 9...a5 mainline.} a5 (10... b6 $6 11. g4 $1 $36)) 9. b3 Nb8 $1 {Black needs to improve the position with Nbd7-b6-Bb7 (or Ba6).} (9... Re8 $2 {Looks normal, but it's a positional mistake:} 10. Bb2 Bf8 11. Bd3 g6 12. Rc1 $16 {[%csl Rc6] Black cannot play with the misplaced knight on c6.}) (9... Ne8 $6 10. Bd3 f5 {f5 is f5, but some players like it. I want to offer you the following idea:} 11. Nb1 $5 $146 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gc3e2] My idea is to continue with Nc3-Ne2, and of course, White is better, at least because we have a Dutch with Black's misplaced knight on c6.}) 10. Bb2 Nbd7 $1 {We already know that g2-g4 is White's idea, that's why Black should act very precisely in order to have enough counterplay against it.} (10... c6 $2 {natural play is bad because after} 11. Bd3 Nbd7 {as was played in the game Karpov-Adams 1992, White missed the winning idea:} 12. g4 $1 $18) (10... b6 $6 {natural move but mistake.} 11. Bd3 Bb7 12. g4 $1 $16 {important move and it secures White a serious advantage.}) 11. Bd3 {[%cal Gg2g4] we are ready for g4.} (11. Rc1 $5 $146 {deserves attention.} c5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Bb5 $14) 11... c5 $1 {very important move.} (11... b6 $2 12. g4 $1 $16) 12. cxd5 $5 {Now we change plan.} (12. g4 {suddenly, the engine shows that Black has enough counterplay:} a4 $1 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Rb3b4] thanks to the move c5, we don't have b4 now.} 13. bxa4 h6 {unclear, you can try to analyze it, but engine thinks that Black is ok.} 14. g5 hxg5 15. Nxg5 cxd4 16. exd4 Bd6 $13) 12... exd5 13. O-O b6 {Engine doesn't show too much, just +0,30, but OTB it's definitely a pleasant position:} 14. Nb1 $5 $146 {my recommendation: we will improve our knight on c3:} (14. Ne5 Bb7 15. Rad1 $14 {it's a normal way to continue.}) (14. e4 $5 {deserves attention.}) 14... Bb7 15. Nc3 Rc8 16. Rfd1 $14 {Typical, slightly better position. We can conclude by saying that we have a very nice and pleasant game against 4...d5.} *

