{[%evp 0,20,26,26,38,6,43,29,17,8,1,4,4,13,24,26,29,22,24,24,25,21,15]} 1. d4 e6 {In the third part of the database, we should focus on the 1...e6 move order, related to 2...Bb4+, because there are some differences. First of all, what is our reply against 1...e6?} 2. c4 {It is the most coherent response with our repertoire.} (2. e4 {You can play the French, but not all players are ready to do it.}) (2. Nf3 {Of course, after 2...Nf6 or 2...d5, you transpose, but Black can play other lines:} c5 $5 {could be problematic for our repertoire.} (2... b6 {is one extra option, but} 3. e4 $14 {[%cal Gf1d3] It shouldn't be problematic.}) 3. e4 {is probably the best, but then you need to know the Sicilian.} (3. c4 {is nothing for White.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 $11) (3. e3 {You can play the Colle, but it is also nothing.} Nf6 $11) (3. c3 {is too passive.} d5 $11) 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 {And probably not everybody here is ready to play the Sicilian.}) 2... Bb4+ {Black has also other moves, but this is the focus of our database.} 3. Nd2 {was the main focus of the second part of our database, and also in accordance with the rest of the Dreev 1.d4 for White repertoire, but now there is a big problem in this move order.} (3. Nc3 {We exclude it, because it is not part of the repertoire, at the very least because of} Nf6 {And we don't play the Nimzo.}) 3... c5 $1 {is a very strong move.} (3... Nf6 4. Ngf3 {At minimum we can transpose.} (4. a3 $5 {could be even stronger.})) 4. a3 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 {We need to take with the queen.} (5. Bxd2 $6 {Now this move is nothing.} cxd4 6. Nf3 {And instead of Nf6, Black can play} Nc6 {To protect the d4 pawn.} 7. b4 {Probably White is not worse, but also not better for sure.} d6 8. b5 {No games here.} Ne5 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. e3 $44 {Maximum compensation, but most likely it will be a repetition after} Nf6 11. exd4 Qxd4 12. Be3 Qc3+ 13. Bd2 Qd4 $11) 5... cxd4 6. Nf3 (6. Qxd4 {I don't like it, because after} Nf6 $132 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb8c6] Nc6 will come with tempo against the queen.}) 6... Nf6 {And we tranpose to a line, that it's fine for Black. That's why the 1...e6 move order is a bit tricky for us.} 7. Nxd4 d5 {This is the game Grischuk-Kramnik, 2024.} 8. cxd5 Qxd5 9. f3 e5 10. Nc2 Qb3 $11 {Black is fine. That's why I recommend you to go for 3.Bd2 in case of this move order.} *

