1. d4 e6 2. c4 Bb4+ {This file will be useful for players who either want to transpose into Section 1 as soon as possible or prefer to keep the lines as independent as they can—whether due to a maximalist approach or a preference for playing 4.Nd2 in the main Bogo-Indian.} 3. Bd2 Bxd2+ (3... Be7 {First good news: Be7 is now bad because of} 4. e4 $16) (3... c5 4. Bxb4 cxb4 {Option 2: play} 5. Nd2 {and keep it independent!} ({Option 1: play} 5. Nf3 {and Black has nothing better than} Nf6 {and it directly transposes to Section 1.}) (5. e4 $6 {not immediately because of} d5 $132) 5... Nf6 (5... d5 {[%csl Gd2] now the knight on d2 is good:} 6. Ngf3 Nf6 7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3 $14) 6. e4 {only now e4, because we will have e4-e5 with tempo in case of d7-d5.} d6 {now, we have two options:} (6... d5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e5 $16 {[%csl Rf6]}) 7. Qa4+ {good enough for a better endgame:} (7. f4 $5 $146 {[%cal Gg1f3] interesting novelty.}) 7... Nc6 8. d5 Qa5 9. Qxa5 Nxa5 10. Ngf3 $14) (3... a5 {here, everybody will need to transpose in Section 1, but only in a small part of Chapter 7!} 4. a3 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 Nf6 (5... d6 $6 {dubious because of} 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. e4 $16) {Now, I suggest to start with} 6. Nc3 {for everybody, because our idea is e4.} d5 (6... O-O $6 7. e4 $14) 7. Nf3 {We transpose to Section 1, but only in the part where Black plays d7-d5.}) (3... Qe7 {OPTION 1: play} 4. Nf3 {and be ready to transpose in Section 1.} ({Option 2: Keep it independent!} 4. e4 $5 d5 {necessary move.} (4... Nf6 $6 5. Bd3 $16) 5. e5 Nc6 6. a3 $5 $146 {no games already.} Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 dxc4 8. Bxc4 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7g2] most logical plan for Black is b6-Bb7-000.} 9. Nf3 Bb7 10. Nc3 O-O-O 11. Rd1 $1 {important prophylactic move.} (11. O-O $2 {bad because of} Na5 $1 $15 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Gb7f3,Ga5b3]}) 11... Nh6 {probably the best.} (11... Na5 {doesn't make sense now just because of} 12. Be2 $16 {[%csl Ra5] and because of our move Rd1, Black doesn't have the Nb3 fork.}) 12. Qe2 $1 {another strong prophylactic move. Our idea is now d5.} (12. O-O $6 Nf5 $13) 12... g5 $1 {strong move, but as you can see we are already many moves far from the official theory.} (12... Nf5 13. d5 $14 {better for White.}) 13. h3 Kb8 14. d5 exd5 15. Nxd5 $36 {if Black plays well, then he might solve the problems, but White still has an initiative.}) 4... Nf6 (4... f5 {extra line for Black. Playable, but for sure not equalizing.} 5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gd2c1,Gd2f4]} Bxd2 8. Qxd2 d6 (8... Ne4 9. Qc2 d6 10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. Qxc3 Nd7 12. Rfe1 Nf6 13. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Ge2e4] e4 next, and this is for sure at least slightly better for us, for example:} e5 14. e4 f4 15. gxf4 Nh5 {Black's best moves according to the engine.} 16. f5 Bd7 17. Nf3 Rae8 18. Rad1 Nf4 $1 {now starts a forced line.} 19. dxe5 dxe5 20. Qxe5 Qxe5 21. Nxe5 Rxe5 22. Rxd7 Rfxf5 23. Bf1 Rf7 24. Rd8+ Rf8 25. Rxf8+ Kxf8 26. f3 $14 {holdable for the engine, but OTB this is an extra pawn.}) 9. Nc3 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ge6e5,Gc7c6,Gd6d5]} Nc6 (9... c6 10. Rfe1 d5 11. e3 $14 {[%cal Gc3e2,Ge2f4,Gf4d3] good version for White of the Stonewall.}) 10. Rad1 e5 11. Nd5 $1 $16) 5. g3 {directly transposes in Section 1.}) 4. Qxd2 Nf6 (4... f5 {possible, but for sure we will be slightly better:} 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. g3 O-O 7. Bg2 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gd7d6] Black has 2 plans: d5 in Stonewall spirit, or d6 in Classical Dutch spirit.} d6 (7... d5 8. Nf3 c6 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Qc2 {[%csl Gc2] queen on d2 was bad.} Ne4 11. e3 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Ye5][%cal Gc3e2,Ge2f4,Gf4d3,Gb7b6,Gc4d5,Gc6d5,Ga1c1,Gc2c7] very good version for White of the Stonewall.}) 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. Rd1 $1 {[%cal Yd8e7] First, we want to provoke Qe7.} (9. O-O e5 10. d5 Ne7 $132 {[%csl Ge7] e7 is a very good square for the knight.}) 9... Qe7 10. O-O e5 {and now we have} 11. Nd5 $1 $16) {Option 2: play} 5. Nc3 {and keep it independent!} ({OPTION 1: just play} 5. Nf3 {and directly transpose to Section 1.}) 5... d5 (5... O-O $6 {allows} 6. e4 {which is for sure good for White, for example:} d5 7. e5 Ne4 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Qe3 c5 10. O-O-O cxd4 11. Qxe4 $14) 6. cxd5 exd5 7. e3 {we can try to play a good version of the Carlsbad.} O-O (7... Bf5 {against Bd3, but now we can play} 8. f3 $1 $146 {[%cal Gg2g4] we prepare g4.} h5 {[%csl Rh5] Black should stop g4, but we can now play against Black's pawn on h5, for example:} (8... O-O $6 9. g4 $16 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gg1e2]}) 9. O-O-O {[%csl Re8][%cal Ge3e4]} O-O {[%csl Rh5]} 10. h3 $36 {[%cal Gg2g4] g4 ideas, it's a new position that looks very interesting.}) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gg1e2]} (8. Nge2 $5 $146 c6 9. Nf4 {deserves attention.}) 8... Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e7,Yc8f5] most common continuation, with the idea Ne7-Bf5.} 9. Nge2 Ne7 {[%cal Gc8f5] Black wants to exchange the bishops on f5.} 10. Qc2 g6 {[%cal Gc8f5] There are two games here—Basso-Moroni (my game) and Wojtaszek-Vocaturo—but neither Wojtaszek nor I managed to find the best move.} 11. O-O-O $1 $146 {[%csl Re7,Rg6][%cal Rc8f5,Gh2h4,Gf2f3,Gg2g4,Gh4h5] we can play against g6:} Bf5 12. f3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 c6 14. e4 $14 {[%cal Gc1b1]} *

